var tafsirData_7 = {
  1: {
    "Alif-Lãm-Mĩm-Ṣãd": "These are among the disconnected letters (Huroof al-Muqatta'at) that appear at the beginning of certain chapters of the Quran. Their exact meaning is known only to Allah. Some scholars say they serve to capture attention, demonstrate the miraculous nature of the Quran (which is composed of such letters yet cannot be imitated), and remind us that there are matters of the unseen that only Allah knows. They humble us before divine knowledge."
  },
  2: {
    "˹This is˺ a Book sent down to you ˹O Prophet˺": "This Quran is a divine revelation sent down from Allah to Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him). It is not from human authorship but from the Creator of the heavens and earth. This establishes the authority and truthfulness of the message that follows.",
    "do not let anxiety into your heart regarding it": "Allah comforts His Prophet, telling him not to feel distressed, worried, or hesitant about conveying this message. The Prophet might have felt concerned about how people would react or whether he could fulfill this enormous responsibility. Allah reassures him that he should deliver the message with confidence. This teaches us that when we are tasked with speaking the truth, we should not let fear of people's reactions hold us back.",
    "so with it you may warn ˹the disbelievers˺": "One of the primary purposes of the Quran is to serve as a warning to those who disbelieve or disobey Allah. It alerts them to the consequences of rejecting truth, the reality of the Day of Judgment, and the punishment that awaits those who persist in wrongdoing. A warning is an act of mercy—it gives people a chance to change before it is too late.",
    "and as a reminder to the believers": "For those who already believe, the Quran serves as a continuous reminder. Believers are not perfect; they need constant reminders to stay on the right path, to increase their faith, and to remember Allah's commands and promises. Just as a phone needs regular charging, our faith needs the Quran to keep it alive and strong."
  },
  3: {
    "Follow what has been sent down to you from your Lord": "This is a direct command to all of humanity to follow the guidance that Allah has revealed. This guidance is not arbitrary rules but comes from your Lord—the One who created you, knows what is best for you, and wants good for you. Following His guidance is the path to success in this life and the next. Just as a manufacturer provides a manual for a product, Allah provides guidance for the human being He created.",
    "and do not take others as guardians besides Him": "Do not take anyone or anything else as your ultimate authority, protector, or guide besides Allah. This includes false gods, ideologies, cultural practices that contradict divine guidance, or even your own desires when they conflict with what Allah has commanded. Taking others as guardians means giving them the loyalty, obedience, and devotion that belongs only to Allah.",
    "How seldom are you mindful!": "This is a gentle rebuke from Allah, pointing out that humans rarely reflect and remember these truths. We get caught up in daily life, distractions, and worldly pursuits, forgetting our purpose and our Creator. This phrase is a wake-up call to be more conscious and thoughtful about our relationship with Allah."
  },
  4: {
    "˹Imagine˺ how many societies We have destroyed!": "Allah draws our attention to history and the many civilizations that were destroyed because of their rejection of truth and their persistence in wrongdoing. This includes the people of Noah, Aad, Thamud, the people of Lot, and Pharaoh's people. Their ruins still exist as reminders. Allah is showing that He has power over all nations, and no society is too powerful to escape His punishment if they persist in disobedience.",
    "Our torment took them by surprise ˹while sleeping˺ at night or midday": "The punishment came suddenly, when they least expected it—either at night while they slept peacefully or during the middle of the day when they were resting during the afternoon. This teaches us that we should never feel so secure that we think we are beyond Allah's reach. It also shows that punishment can come at any time, so we should always be in a state of obedience and readiness."
  },
  5: {
    "Their only cry—when overwhelmed by Our torment—was, \"We have indeed been wrongdoers.\"": "When the punishment finally came, there was no more denial, no more excuses, no more arrogance. They immediately confessed that they had been wrongdoers. But this confession came too late—it was made at a time when repentance was no longer accepted. This teaches us a profound lesson: the time to acknowledge our mistakes and repent is now, while we still have the opportunity, not when punishment is already upon us. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said that Allah accepts the repentance of a servant as long as the soul has not reached the throat (at the moment of death)."
  },
  6: {
    "We will surely question those who received messengers": "On the Day of Judgment, Allah will question every nation and every individual to whom messengers were sent. They will be asked: Did you receive the message? Did you follow it? How did you respond to the messengers? This establishes that no one can claim ignorance if they received the message. Allah's justice ensures that everyone is given a chance to know the truth before being held accountable.",
    "and We will question the messengers ˹themselves˺": "Even the messengers will be questioned—not because they did anything wrong, but to establish testimony. They will be asked: Did you deliver the message? How did your people respond? The messengers will testify about what they conveyed and how their people reacted. This shows the thoroughness of Allah's justice. As mentioned in Surah Al-Ma'idah (5:109), Allah will gather the messengers and ask them about the response they received from their people."
  },
  7: {
    "Then We will give them a full account with sure knowledge": "Allah will narrate to everyone exactly what they did, with complete and perfect knowledge. Nothing will be hidden, forgotten, or misrepresented. Every deed, word, and intention will be laid bare. This full account will leave no room for denial or argument.",
    "for We were never absent": "Allah was always present, watching and recording everything. Unlike human witnesses who might miss details or forget, Allah is the All-Seeing, All-Knowing, who never sleeps nor is unaware of anything. This is both a warning (that we are always being watched) and a comfort (that Allah knows our struggles and sincere efforts even when no one else sees them)."
  },
  8: {
    "The weighing on that Day will be just": "On the Day of Judgment, there will be scales to weigh people's deeds, and this weighing will be absolutely fair and just. There will be no injustice, no favoritism, no bribery, and no mistakes. Every good deed, no matter how small, will be counted, and every bad deed will also be accounted for. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: \"Do not belittle any good deed, even meeting your brother with a cheerful face\" (Muslim). This encourages us to do good consistently.",
    "As for those whose scale will be heavy ˹with good deeds˺": "Those whose good deeds outweigh their bad deeds will have heavy scales. The weight comes from the sincerity, quality, and quantity of good actions. Saying \"SubhanAllah\" (Glory be to Allah) and \"Alhamdulillah\" (All praise is due to Allah) are described by the Prophet (peace be upon him) as heavy on the scales but light on the tongue.",
    "˹only˺ they will be successful": "True success—the only success that ultimately matters—is achieved by those whose scales are heavy with good. This success means salvation from Hell, entry into Paradise, and the pleasure of Allah. All worldly success means nothing if one fails this ultimate test."
  },
  9: {
    "But those whose scale is light": "Those whose bad deeds outweigh their good deeds, or who have no good deeds to show, will have light scales. This is a terrifying outcome because it indicates failure in the ultimate test of life.",
    "they have doomed themselves": "They have caused their own destruction. Allah did not wrong them; they wronged themselves through their choices. They had the same opportunity as everyone else to do good and avoid evil, but they wasted it. This personal accountability is central to Islamic belief—everyone is responsible for their own soul.",
    "for wrongfully denying Our signs": "The reason for their loss is that they rejected, denied, or ignored Allah's signs. These signs include the Quran, the teachings of the prophets, the natural world that points to Allah's existence, and the inner conscience that guides toward good. Denying these signs is a form of injustice (dhulm) because it is a violation of truth and a betrayal of one's own soul."
  },
  10: {
    "We have indeed established you on earth": "Allah reminds humanity that He has given us a place on this earth, establishing us with stability, power, and authority. We are not here by accident but by divine placement. He has made the earth suitable for human life—with the right atmosphere, gravity, water, and resources.",
    "and provided you with a means of livelihood": "Allah has created countless ways for us to sustain ourselves—through agriculture, trade, professions, natural resources, and more. Every bite of food we eat, every breath we take, is a provision from Allah.",
    "˹Yet˺ you seldom give any thanks": "Despite all these blessings, humans rarely show gratitude to Allah. We take these blessings for granted, complaining about what we lack rather than appreciating what we have. True gratitude is shown not just by words but by using Allah's blessings in ways that please Him."
  },
  11: {
    "Surely We created you,": "Allah created humanity, beginning with Adam (peace be upon him), whom He fashioned from clay. This creation was a deliberate, honored act—not random or accidental.",
    "then shaped you,": "After creating the basic form, Allah shaped humanity into its beautiful and functional form—with eyes to see, ears to hear, limbs to move, and minds to think. This shaping was done with perfect design and wisdom.",
    "then said to the angels, \"Prostrate before Adam,\"": "Allah commanded the angels to prostrate before Adam as a sign of honor and respect for this new creation. This prostration was not worship (which is only for Allah) but a gesture of acknowledgment of Adam's special status and obedience to Allah's command.",
    "so they all did—but not Iblîs,": "All the angels obeyed immediately, but Iblis (Satan) refused. Though Iblis was living among the angels due to his extensive worship, he was actually from the jinn (created from fire). When the test came, his true nature was revealed.",
    "who refused to prostrate with the others": "Iblis deliberately disobeyed Allah's direct command. This was not a mistake or oversight—it was willful rebellion driven by pride. This moment marks the beginning of Iblis's fall from grace and his eternal enmity toward humanity."
  },
  12: {
    "Allah asked, \"What prevented you from prostrating when I commanded you?\"": "Allah questioned Iblis, giving him a chance to explain himself. This shows that even in divine judgment, there is an opportunity to respond. Allah already knew the answer, but the question was asked so that Iblis's reasoning would be exposed and recorded.",
    "He replied, \"I am better than he is:": "This is the core of Iblis's sin—arrogance and pride. He believed himself superior to Adam and therefore felt he should not have to bow. This self-perception of superiority led him to disobey a direct command from Allah. Pride (kibr) is thus shown to be an extremely dangerous sin that can lead to rejecting truth even when it comes directly from Allah.",
    "You created me from fire and him from clay.\"": "Iblis's reasoning was based on the material of creation—fire seems more impressive than clay. But this reasoning is deeply flawed. First, the value of a creation is determined by Allah, not by the material used. Second, clay has qualities (stability, growth, humility) that are superior in many ways to fire (which is destructive and unstable). Third, and most importantly, when Allah commands something, our job is to obey, not to debate or rationalize. This teaches us that human logic, when used to disobey Allah, becomes a tool of destruction."
  },
  13: {
    "Allah said, \"Then get down from Paradise!": "Because of his arrogance and disobedience, Allah immediately expelled Iblis from his elevated position. There was no second chance given for this willful rebellion. This shows the severity of arrogance in Allah's sight.",
    "It is not for you to be arrogant here.": "Paradise is a place of purity and humility. Arrogance has no place there. Anyone who carries pride in their heart cannot remain in such a blessed place. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: \"No one who has an atom's weight of arrogance in his heart will enter Paradise\" (Muslim).",
    "So get out! You are truly one of the disgraced.\"": "Iblis, who sought to be honored above Adam, ended up being disgraced. This is the irony of arrogance—those who seek to elevate themselves through pride end up being humiliated. True honor comes from humility and obedience to Allah."
  },
  14: {
    "He appealed, \"Then delay my end until the Day of their resurrection.\"": "Instead of repenting or asking for forgiveness, Iblis asked for more time. His intention was not to use this time for repentance but to lead humans astray. This shows that his heart was completely hardened. He was not sorry for what he did; he was only planning further evil. This is a warning about the danger of persistence in sin—it can harden the heart to the point where repentance becomes unthinkable."
  },
  15: {
    "Allah said, \"You are delayed ˹until the appointed Day˺.\"": "Allah granted Iblis's request, allowing him to live until the Day of Judgment. This was not a favor to Iblis but part of Allah's divine plan. Through this test, believers would be distinguished from disbelievers, and those who resist Satan's temptations would be rewarded. Allah's granting this request shows His supreme confidence in His plan and His knowledge that true believers will overcome Satan's plots."
  },
  16: {
    "He said, \"For leaving me to stray": "Iblis blamed Allah for his own misguidance, refusing to take responsibility for his choice. This is a tactic still used today—blaming circumstances, others, or even Allah for one's own sinful choices. The truth is that Iblis chose to disobey; Allah only allowed him to face the consequences of his choice.",
    "I will lie in ambush for them on Your Straight Path.\"": "Iblis declared his strategy: he would sit on the Straight Path—the path of guidance that leads to Allah—and try to divert people from it. This tells us that Satan focuses his efforts on those trying to do good. He is less concerned with those already far from Allah. The closer you try to get to Allah, the harder Satan works to stop you. This is why practicing Muslims often face more temptations and challenges—they are targets."
  },
  17: {
    "I will approach them from their front,": "Satan attacks from the front by making people anxious about the future, causing them to fear poverty, death, or failure, leading them to compromise their faith for worldly security.",
    "their back,": "He attacks from behind by making people attached to their past—whether through nostalgia for sinful times, pride in ancestry, or clinging to harmful traditions.",
    "their right,": "He attacks from the right (the side of good deeds) by making people proud of their worship, showing off, or corrupting their good intentions.",
    "their left,": "He attacks from the left (the side of sin) by beautifying sins and making them seem harmless or enjoyable.",
    "and then You will find most of them ungrateful.\"": "Satan's ultimate goal is to make people ungrateful to Allah. Ingratitude leads to disbelief and sin. Notice he said \"most of them\"—not all. This is an admission that some will resist his plots. Be among those few who remain grateful and steadfast."
  },
  18: {
    "Allah said, \"Get out of Paradise!": "Allah reaffirms the expulsion of Iblis. There is no room for negotiation or reversal. The decision is final.",
    "You are disgraced and rejected!": "Iblis is cursed, dishonored, and removed from Allah's mercy. The one who sought to be superior is now the lowest of the low.",
    "I will certainly fill up Hell with you and your followers all together.\"": "Allah declares that Hell will be filled with Satan and all who follow him. This is a promise and a warning. Those who choose to follow Satan's path—through arrogance, disobedience, and ingratitude—will share his fate. But this also means that those who resist Satan and follow Allah's guidance will be saved from this fate."
  },
  19: {
    "˹Allah said,˺ \"O Adam! Live with your wife in Paradise": "Allah honored Adam and his wife (Hawwa/Eve) by placing them in Paradise, a place of perfect comfort, beauty, and peace. They were given a blessed home as a starting point for humanity.",
    "and eat from wherever you please,": "They had complete freedom to enjoy the countless blessings of Paradise. Everything was permissible for them—a vast abundance of fruits, foods, and pleasures. Allah's commands are not about restriction but about guidance within a framework of abundance.",
    "but do not approach this tree,": "Among all the trees in Paradise, only one was forbidden. The prohibition was simple and clear. This was a test of obedience—would they listen to Allah or give in to temptation? Note that the command was \"do not approach,\" not just \"do not eat.\" This teaches us that Islam often prohibits the means that lead to sin, not just the sin itself (like lowering the gaze to prevent adultery).",
    "or else you will be wrongdoers.\"": "Allah warned them of the consequence of disobedience—they would become wrongdoers (zalimeen). This warning was given in advance, out of mercy, so they had full knowledge of what was at stake."
  },
  20: {
    "Then Satan tempted them": "Satan approached Adam and Eve with whispers (waswasa)—subtle suggestions that planted doubt and desire in their hearts. This is how Satan works: not with obvious evil but with gradual, seemingly harmless suggestions.",
    "in order to expose what was hidden of their nakedness.": "Part of Satan's goal was to strip them of their honor and covering. In Paradise, they were clothed in dignity. Satan wanted to humiliate them and expose their vulnerability. This connects physical nakedness with spiritual vulnerability—when we sin, we lose our spiritual covering.",
    "He said, \"Your Lord has forbidden this tree to you only to prevent you from becoming angels or immortals.\"": "Satan lied, twisting Allah's command and suggesting a false motive. He implied that Allah was withholding something good from them out of jealousy or control. This is a classic satanic tactic—making Allah's commands seem like arbitrary restrictions rather than loving guidance. He appealed to their desires for immortality and higher status."
  },
  21: {
    "And he swore to them, \"I am truly your sincere advisor.\"": "Satan took an oath, swearing that he was giving them sincere advice. Adam and Eve could not imagine that anyone would swear by Allah while lying. This teaches us that deceptive people often appear sincere and trustworthy. They use religious language and oaths to gain trust. We must judge advice by its alignment with Allah's commands, not by how sincere the advisor appears."
  },
  22: {
    "So he brought about their fall through deception.": "Satan's deception worked. Through his lies, false oaths, and persistent whispers, he caused Adam and Eve to slip from their obedience. The word used (dalla) suggests a gradual lowering—sin often happens step by step, not all at once.",
    "And when they tasted of the tree, their nakedness was exposed to them,": "The moment they sinned, the immediate consequence was the loss of their covering. Their nakedness became apparent to them, symbolizing the loss of innocence and the shame that follows disobedience. Sin strips away our dignity and protection.",
    "prompting them to cover themselves with leaves from Paradise.": "Their immediate reaction was to try to cover themselves using the leaves of Paradise. This shows the natural human sense of shame (haya) and the instinct to preserve dignity. Even in their fallen state, they sought covering.",
    "Then their Lord called out to them, \"Did I not forbid you from that tree": "Allah addressed them directly, reminding them of His clear command. This question was not for information but for acknowledgment—to make them reflect on what they had done.",
    "and ˹did I not˺ tell you that Satan is your sworn enemy?\"": "Allah had warned them about Satan's enmity. He reminded them that the warning had been given clearly. This teaches us that Allah always warns us before any test, and when we fail, we cannot claim we did not know."
  },
  23: {
    "They replied, \"Our Lord! We have wronged ourselves.": "Adam and Eve immediately took responsibility for their sin. They did not blame Satan, each other, or Allah. They acknowledged that they had wronged themselves. This is the first step of true repentance—accepting personal responsibility.",
    "If You do not forgive us and have mercy on us,": "They turned to Allah, seeking His forgiveness and mercy. They recognized that forgiveness is entirely in Allah's hands and that they desperately needed it. This shows humility and complete dependence on Allah.",
    "we will certainly be losers.\"": "They acknowledged that without Allah's forgiveness, they would be utterly lost. There is no salvation except through Allah's mercy. This beautiful supplication is a model for us when we sin—acknowledge the wrong, take responsibility, seek Allah's forgiveness, and recognize our complete need for His mercy."
  },
  24: {
    "Allah said, \"Descend as enemies to each other.": "Allah commanded Adam, Eve, and Satan to descend to earth. The enmity mentioned is primarily between humans and Satan, who will be enemies until the Day of Judgment. There is also a general struggle and conflict in earthly life that did not exist in Paradise.",
    "You will find in the earth a residence and provision for your appointed stay.\"": "Earth would be their temporary home, where they would find what they need to live. But it is temporary—for an appointed time. This reminds us that our time on earth is limited and that this world is not our permanent home. We are here for a purpose and will eventually return to Allah."
  },
  25: {
    "He added, \"There you will live,": "On earth, you will spend your lives—working, worshipping, being tested, experiencing joy and hardship.",
    "there you will die,": "And on earth, every soul will taste death. This is an inescapable reality that should remind us to prepare for what comes after.",
    "and from there you will be resurrected.\"": "And from the earth, on the Day of Judgment, all human beings will be raised to face their Lord. This completes the cycle: created from earth, living on earth, dying and being buried in earth, and then resurrected from earth for eternal judgment."
  },
  26: {
    "O children of Adam!": "This address to all of humanity connects us to the story just mentioned. We are all descendants of Adam, and the lessons from his experience apply to us.",
    "We have provided for you clothing to cover your nakedness": "Allah has blessed humanity with the means to make clothing that covers our bodies and preserves our dignity. This is a mercy from Allah—animals do not have this, but humans have been given the intelligence and resources to clothe themselves.",
    "and as an adornment.": "Clothing is not only for covering but also for beautification. Islam allows and even encourages people to look good and dress well, within the bounds of modesty. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said, \"Allah is beautiful and loves beauty\" (Muslim).",
    "However, the best clothing is righteousness.": "While physical clothing covers the body, the clothing of taqwa (God-consciousness, righteousness, piety) covers and protects the soul. This is the most important covering. A person may be dressed in expensive clothes but have a naked soul due to lack of righteousness. Conversely, a person in simple clothes but with strong taqwa is truly well-covered.",
    "This is one of Allah's bounties, so perhaps you will be mindful.": "Both types of clothing—physical and spiritual—are blessings from Allah. We should be grateful for them and be mindful of maintaining both our physical modesty and our spiritual purity."
  },
  27: {
    "O children of Adam! Do not let Satan deceive you": "This is a direct warning to all of humanity. Be on guard against Satan's tricks. Do not be naive about his tactics or think you are immune to his deception.",
    "as he tempted your parents out of Paradise": "Remember what happened to your ancestors, Adam and Eve. Satan caused them to lose Paradise. Do not let him do the same to you. Learn from their experience.",
    "and caused their cover to be removed in order to expose their nakedness.": "Part of Satan's strategy was to strip them of their dignity. He does the same today—promoting shamelessness, immodesty, and the erosion of natural modesty. Societies that abandon modesty are following Satan's agenda.",
    "Surely he and his soldiers watch you from where you cannot see them.": "This is a sobering reminder: Satan and his army of devils can see us, but we cannot see them. They watch for opportunities to mislead us, knowing our weaknesses. This should make us vigilant and turn to Allah for protection constantly. The Prophet (peace be upon him) taught us to seek refuge in Allah from Satan regularly.",
    "We have made the devils allies of those who disbelieve.": "Those who choose to reject faith will find Satan as their companion and ally. This is not a reward but a punishment—they will be led further astray by their own choosing. The relationship between disbelievers and devils is mutual: they support each other in falsehood."
  },
  28: {
    "Whenever they commit a shameful deed,": "When people engage in immoral or sinful actions—whether sexual immorality, injustice, or other shameful behavior—",
    "they say, \"We found our forefathers doing it": "They justify their actions by pointing to tradition and ancestral practice. \"This is our culture,\" \"Our parents did it,\" \"It has always been done this way.\" This excuse removes personal responsibility and blindly follows the past, even when it contradicts truth.",
    "and Allah has commanded us to do it.\"": "Even worse, some attribute their sinful practices to Allah, claiming religious sanction for what they do. This is a serious lie against Allah.",
    "Say, \"No! Allah never commands what is shameful.": "The Prophet is instructed to clearly reject this claim. Allah's nature is pure, and His commands are always good. He never orders shameful, immoral, or evil actions. Anyone claiming otherwise is lying about Allah.",
    "How can you attribute to Allah what you do not know?\"": "This rhetorical question challenges them: How dare you speak about Allah without knowledge? Lying about Allah is one of the gravest sins. We must be careful never to claim something is from Allah unless we have clear evidence from revelation."
  },
  29: {
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"My Lord has commanded uprightness": "In contrast to their false claims, here is what Allah actually commands: justice, fairness, and balance (qist) in all affairs. Islam teaches moderation and justice in everything.",
    "and dedication ˹to Him alone˺ in worship,": "Direct your worship—your prayers, your attention, your heart—toward Allah alone at every place of prayer. Be fully present when you worship, facing Him with your entire being.",
    "calling upon Him with sincere devotion.": "When you make dua (supplication) or worship, do so with pure sincerity, dedicating your religion exclusively to Allah. Sincerity (ikhlas) is the soul of worship. Without it, even abundant acts of worship are hollow.",
    "Just as He first brought you into being, you will be brought to life again.\"": "Just as Allah created you the first time from nothing, He will resurrect you. The One who created you once can certainly create you again. This is a logical argument for the resurrection—it is actually easier than the first creation, yet even the first creation was no difficulty for Allah."
  },
  30: {
    "He has guided some,": "Allah, in His wisdom, has guided a group of people to the truth. They accepted guidance when it came to them, and Allah blessed them with faith and righteousness.",
    "while others are destined to stray.": "Another group has misguidance confirmed upon them. This is not arbitrary—it is because of their own choices. They chose to reject truth, and so Allah allowed them to remain in their misguidance as a consequence.",
    "They have taken devils as their masters instead of Allah—": "The reason for their misguidance is that they chose to follow Satan and his suggestions instead of following Allah. They made devils their allies, protectors, and guides.",
    "thinking they are ˹rightly˺ guided.\"": "The most tragic part is that they believe they are on the right path. They are confidently wrong, deceived into thinking their falsehood is truth. This is the ultimate deception of Satan—to make people feel good about their misguidance. This is why we must constantly ask Allah for guidance and check our beliefs and actions against the Quran and Sunnah, not just our feelings."
  },
  31: {
    "O Children of Adam! Dress properly whenever you are at worship.": "Allah commands us to beautify ourselves and dress appropriately when coming to prayer and places of worship. This includes wearing clean, modest, and dignified clothing. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said that Allah is more deserving of us beautifying ourselves for Him than for anyone else. This verse was also revealed to correct the practice of some pre-Islamic Arabs who used to perform pilgrimage naked, thinking it was more humble. Islam teaches that proper covering is part of worship, not contrary to it.",
    "Eat and drink,": "Allah permits us to enjoy food and drink. These are blessings from Him, and enjoying them is not sinful. Islam is not a religion of deprivation—it allows and encourages enjoying the good things Allah has provided.",
    "but do not waste.": "However, there must be limits. Excess and extravagance are prohibited. Whether it is food, drink, money, or any resource, wasting it is sinful. This includes overeating, throwing away food, and excessive spending on luxuries while others go hungry.",
    "Surely He does not like the wasteful.": "Allah explicitly states His displeasure with those who waste. This is a clear warning. If we want Allah's love, we must practice moderation and avoid extravagance. The Prophet (peace be upon him) taught us to eat to fill one-third of our stomach with food, one-third with water, and leave one-third for air. This balanced approach protects both our physical and spiritual health."
  },
  32: {
    "Ask, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"Who has forbidden the adornments and lawful provisions Allah has brought forth for His servants?\"": "This is a rhetorical challenge to those who make things unlawful without Allah's authority. Some people, whether from extreme religious practices or cultural innovations, prohibit things that Allah has made permissible—like certain foods, clothing, or enjoyments. Allah asks: by what authority do you forbid what He has allowed? Only Allah has the right to declare something forbidden.",
    "Say, \"They are for the enjoyment of the believers in this worldly life,": "Allah clarifies that these blessings—good food, beautiful clothing, lawful pleasures—are meant to be enjoyed by believers in this world. Islam does not demand monks or ascetics who deprive themselves of all worldly goods. Believers can and should enjoy Allah's provisions while being grateful and moderate.",
    "but they will be exclusively theirs on the Day of Judgment.": "In this world, both believers and disbelievers enjoy Allah's provisions. But in the Hereafter, all pure blessings will be exclusively for the believers. The disbelievers will have no share in the pleasures of Paradise.",
    "This is how We make Our revelations clear for people of knowledge.\"": "Allah makes His guidance clear and detailed for those who seek to understand. True knowledge leads to recognizing that Allah's laws are balanced—neither extreme permissiveness nor extreme restriction."
  },
  33: {
    "Say, \"My Lord has only forbidden open and secret indecencies,": "Allah clarifies what is actually forbidden. First: indecent and shameful acts, whether done publicly or privately. There is no difference between sins committed in public and those hidden—both are forbidden. Allah sees everything, and His prohibition applies regardless of who is watching.",
    "sinfulness,": "All forms of sin and transgression are forbidden. This is a comprehensive term covering any action that goes against Allah's commands.",
    "unjust aggression,": "Oppression, transgression, and harming others without right are forbidden. Islam stands firmly against injustice in all its forms—whether against individuals, communities, or nations.",
    "associating ˹others˺ with Allah ˹in worship˺—a practice He has never authorized—": "Shirk (associating partners with Allah) is the greatest sin. Allah has never given permission for anyone or anything to be worshipped alongside Him. This includes worshipping idols, saints, prophets, or any creation.",
    "and attributing to Allah what you do not know.\"": "Speaking about Allah without knowledge is forbidden. This includes making up religious rulings, claiming something is halal or haram without evidence, or describing Allah in ways He has not described Himself. This sin is listed alongside shirk, showing its severity."
  },
  34: {
    "For each community there is an appointed term.": "Every nation, civilization, and people has a predetermined lifespan set by Allah. No society lasts forever. History shows us the rise and fall of countless civilizations—the Egyptians, Romans, Persians, and many others. Each had its time, and then it ended.",
    "When their time arrives, they can neither delay it for a moment, nor could they advance it.": "When Allah's appointed time comes for a nation's end, there is no escaping it. They cannot postpone it even by a single moment, nor can they bring it forward. This teaches us that ultimate control belongs to Allah alone. Nations that feel invincible should remember that their power is temporary and their end is certain."
  },
  35: {
    "O children of Adam! When messengers from among yourselves come to you reciting My revelations—": "Allah addresses all of humanity, informing them that messengers will be sent from among their own kind—human beings who speak their language and understand their circumstances. These messengers recite Allah's revelations, making the truth clear and accessible.",
    "whoever shuns evil and mends their ways,": "Those who respond properly to the message will avoid forbidden things (taqwa) and reform themselves by doing good deeds. This is the two-part formula for success: staying away from evil AND actively doing good.",
    "there will be no fear for them, nor will they grieve.": "Such people will be given complete security. They will have no fear about their future (in this life or the Hereafter), nor will they grieve over their past. This is the ultimate state of peace—freedom from both anxiety about tomorrow and regret about yesterday. This is the reward for accepting and following divine guidance."
  },
  36: {
    "But those who receive Our revelations with denial and arrogance": "In contrast, those who reject Allah's signs do so for two main reasons: denial (refusing to accept the truth) and arrogance (considering themselves too important to follow). These two traits—lying and pride—are the hallmarks of disbelief.",
    "will be the residents of the Fire.": "Their destination is Hell, where they will not be mere visitors but permanent residents.",
    "They will be there forever.": "Their punishment is eternal, with no end and no escape. This is the consequence of rejecting divine guidance when it was clearly presented to them."
  },
  37: {
    "Who does more wrong than those who fabricate lies against Allah or deny His revelations?": "This rhetorical question establishes that the worst wrongdoers are those who lie about Allah (making up false teachings, inventing religious practices) or those who reject His actual revelations. These are the most unjust of all people.",
    "They will receive what is destined for them,": "They will live out their decreed lifespan and receive their worldly portion as written. Allah does not immediately punish every sinner—He gives them time, which is actually an opportunity to repent, but which they often waste.",
    "until Our messenger-angels arrive to take their souls, asking them, \"Where are those ˹false gods˺ you used to invoke besides Allah?\"": "When death comes and the angels arrive to extract their souls, they will be confronted with a devastating question: Where are the false gods, idols, or other beings you worshipped and called upon? Where are they now to help you?",
    "They will cry, \"They have failed us,\"": "In that moment of truth, they will confess that their false gods have abandoned them, disappeared, and are of no use whatsoever.",
    "and they will confess against themselves that they were indeed disbelievers.": "They will testify against themselves, admitting their disbelief. There will be no more excuses or justifications—only the bitter truth of their misguidance."
  },
  38: {
    "Allah will say, \"Enter the Fire along with the ˹evil˺ groups of jinn and humans that preceded you.\"": "Allah will command these disbelievers to enter Hell, joining previous generations of disbelieving jinn and humans who went before them. Evil is not new—it has a long history, and all who participated will be gathered together.",
    "Whenever a group enters Hell, it will curse the preceding one": "Each group that enters Hell will curse the group that came before them—blaming them for setting bad examples, establishing false traditions, and leading them astray. There will be no solidarity among the people of Hell, only blame and hatred.",
    "until they are all gathered inside, the followers will say about their leaders, \"Our Lord! They have misled us, so multiply their torment in the Fire.\"": "When everyone is assembled, the followers will blame their leaders—the politicians, scholars, celebrities, and influencers who led them away from truth. They will ask Allah to double the punishment of these misleading leaders.",
    "He will answer, \"It has already been multiplied for all, but you do not know.\"": "Allah responds that everyone already has their full, appropriate punishment. The leaders are punished for their own sins plus the sin of misleading others, while the followers are punished for their own choices. But in their anguish, they do not realize this. This teaches us that following bad leaders does not excuse us—we are still responsible for our own choices."
  },
  39: {
    "Then the leaders will say to their followers, \"You were no better than us!": "The leaders will respond to their followers' accusations, pointing out that the followers were not innocent victims. They had their own minds, made their own choices, and willingly followed the path of error. No one forced them.",
    "So taste the torment for what you used to commit.\"": "The leaders tell the followers to accept their punishment as a consequence of their own actions. Everyone will be held accountable for their own choices. This dialogue in Hell shows us that neither blindly following leaders nor being a misleading leader will be excused. Everyone must take personal responsibility for knowing and following the truth."
  },
  40: {
    "Surely those who receive our revelations with denial and arrogance,": "Those who reject Allah's signs and are too proud to accept the truth face a terrible fate.",
    "the gates of heaven will not be opened for them,": "When they die, their souls will not be welcomed in the heavens. The Prophet (peace be upon him) explained that when a believer dies, their soul ascends through the heavens with the gates opening for them, while a disbeliever's soul is rejected and thrown back down. Additionally, their prayers and good deeds (if any) will not be accepted or raised up.",
    "nor will they enter Paradise until a camel passes through the eye of a needle.": "This is a powerful expression of impossibility. A camel—one of the largest animals—passing through the tiny hole in a sewing needle is absolutely impossible. Thus, their entry into Paradise is equally impossible. This should terrify anyone who rejects truth while arrogantly thinking they will be fine.",
    "This is how We reward the wicked.": "This severe consequence is the just recompense for those who willfully reject divine guidance and commit crimes against themselves and others by refusing to believe."
  },
  41: {
    "Hell will be their bed;": "Instead of comfortable beds, they will lie on Hell itself. The fire will be beneath them, serving as their mattress and resting place.",
    "flames will be their cover.": "And above them, instead of blankets or sheets, there will be layers of fire covering them. They will be surrounded by punishment from every direction—below, above, and all around.",
    "This is how We reward the wrongdoers.": "This is the just payment for those who wronged themselves by rejecting truth and wronged others by their injustice. The imagery of bed and cover—usually associated with comfort and security—being replaced by fire emphasizes the complete reversal of their expectations."
  },
  42: {
    "As for those who believe and do good—": "The people of Paradise are characterized by two things: belief in their hearts and good deeds with their limbs. Faith alone without action, or actions without faith, are both incomplete.",
    "We never require of any soul more than what it can afford—": "Allah, in His mercy and justice, does not burden anyone beyond their capacity. Every command of Islam is within human ability to fulfill. If someone truly cannot do something, they are excused or given an alternative. This shows Allah's fairness and compassion. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: \"If I command you to do something, do as much of it as you can.\"",
    "it is they who will be the residents of Paradise.": "Those who believe and do good according to their ability will be the people of Paradise.",
    "They will be there forever.": "Just as the punishment of disbelievers is eternal, so too is the reward of believers. They will never be expelled from Paradise, never experience death there, and never have their blessings taken away."
  },
  43: {
    "We will remove whatever bitterness they had in their hearts.": "In Paradise, Allah will purify the hearts of believers from any grudges, jealousy, resentment, or ill feelings they may have had toward others in this world. There will be no negativity, no old conflicts, and no bad feelings. Everyone will be at peace with everyone else. This is part of the perfection of Paradise—not just physical pleasure but complete emotional and spiritual peace.",
    "Rivers will flow under their feet.": "Paradise will have rivers flowing beneath the residents—rivers of water, milk, honey, and wine (that does not intoxicate). This imagery represents abundance, beauty, and continuous blessing.",
    "And they will say, \"Praise be to Allah for guiding us to this.": "The residents of Paradise will express gratitude to Allah, recognizing that everything they achieved was because of His guidance. This is the attitude of true believers—always attributing success to Allah.",
    "We would have never been guided if Allah had not guided us.": "They acknowledge that without Allah's guidance, they would have been lost. This is humility—knowing that our good deeds, faith, and eventual salvation are all gifts from Allah. We cannot guide ourselves.",
    "The messengers of our Lord had certainly come with the truth.\"": "They will confirm that the messengers spoke the truth. Everything the prophets warned about and promised has come to pass. Those who believed are now vindicated.",
    "It will be announced to them, \"This is Paradise awarded to you for what you used to do.\"": "An announcement will be made confirming that they have earned Paradise through their faith and good deeds. While Paradise is ultimately Allah's mercy (no one's deeds alone can earn it), Allah in His generosity attributes it to their efforts as a reward and honor for them."
  },
  44: {
    "The residents of Paradise will call out to the residents of the Fire, \"We have certainly found our Lord's promise to be true.": "The people of Paradise will call out to those in Hell, confirming that everything Allah promised—the reward, the bliss, the eternal happiness—has come true. They have witnessed it firsthand.",
    "Have you too found your Lord's promise to be true?\"": "They ask the people of Hell if they have also found Allah's warnings to be true. This is not mockery but a confirmation of truth that the people of Hell cannot deny.",
    "They will reply, \"Yes, we have!\"": "The people of Hell will be forced to admit that yes, everything Allah warned about has come true. The punishment, the regret, the eternal suffering—it is all exactly as described. There is no more denial possible.",
    "Then a caller will announce to both, \"May Allah's condemnation be upon the wrongdoers,": "An announcement will be made that Allah's curse is upon those who did wrong. This public declaration confirms the justice of their punishment."
  },
  45: {
    "those who hindered ˹others˺ from Allah's Way,": "The wrongdoers being cursed are those who not only went astray themselves but actively prevented others from following Allah's path. They blocked, discouraged, or fought against guidance reaching people.",
    "strived to make it ˹appear˺ crooked,": "They tried to distort the truth, making the straight path seem wrong, outdated, or unreasonable. They spread doubts and confusion about Allah's religion.",
    "and disbelieved in the Hereafter.\"": "They denied the Day of Judgment, thinking there would be no accountability. This denial allowed them to live without restraint, not caring about consequences. But now they face exactly what they denied."
  },
  46: {
    "There will be a barrier between Paradise and Hell.": "A wall or partition will separate Paradise from Hell, preventing any crossing between them while allowing some communication.",
    "And on the heights ˹of that barrier˺ will be people": "On the elevated part of this barrier (Al-A'raf) will be a group of people. Scholars have different opinions about who they are—some say they are people whose good and bad deeds were exactly equal, so they are waiting; others say they are martyrs, prophets, or angels observing both sides.",
    "who will recognize ˹the residents of˺ both by their appearance.": "These people on the heights can identify the residents of both Paradise and Hell by their features. The people of Paradise will be radiant and beautiful, while the people of Hell will be darkened and humiliated.",
    "They will call out to the residents of Paradise, \"Peace be upon you!\"": "They greet the people of Paradise with the greeting of peace (salaam), showing respect and longing.",
    "They will have not yet entered Paradise, but eagerly hope to.": "At this point, they have not yet entered Paradise, but they have hope that they will. This indicates a state of anticipation and desire for Allah's mercy."
  },
  47: {
    "When their eyes will turn towards the residents of Hell,": "When the people on the heights look toward Hell and see its horrors and the suffering of its inhabitants—",
    "they will pray, \"Our Lord! Do not join us with the wrongdoing people.\"": "They immediately turn to Allah in supplication, begging not to be placed among the wrongdoers in Hell. The sight of Hell's punishment fills them with fear and intensifies their hope for Paradise. This teaches us that contemplating Hell should motivate us to seek Allah's protection."
  },
  48: {
    "Those on the heights will call out to some ˹tyrants in the Fire˺, who they will recognize by their appearance,": "The people on the heights will recognize certain notorious wrongdoers in Hell—perhaps powerful tyrants, arrogant leaders, or well-known oppressors from history.",
    "saying, \"Your large numbers and arrogance are of no use ˹today˺!": "They will address these former powerful people, pointing out that all their followers, wealth, armies, and pride have not saved them from Allah's punishment. Everything they relied upon has proven useless."
  },
  49: {
    "Are these ˹humble believers˺ the ones you swore would never be shown Allah's mercy?\"": "The people on the heights point to the believers in Paradise and ask the tyrants: Are these the poor, weak believers you mocked and swore would never receive anything from Allah? You despised them, yet look where they are now.",
    "˹Finally, those on the heights will be told:˺ \"Enter Paradise! There will be no fear for you, nor will you grieve.\"": "After this scene, the people on the heights are finally admitted to Paradise with the beautiful assurance of no fear and no grief. Allah's mercy encompasses them, and their hopeful waiting is rewarded."
  },
  50: {
    "The residents of the Fire will then cry out to the residents of Paradise, \"Aid us with some water or any provision Allah has granted you.\"": "The people of Hell, in their unbearable thirst and hunger, will desperately call out to the people of Paradise, begging for even a little water or any relief. This shows the extreme desperation of their condition.",
    "They will reply, \"Allah has forbidden both to the disbelievers,": "The people of Paradise will respond that they cannot help—not because they are unwilling, but because Allah has forbidden the provisions of Paradise from reaching the disbelievers. The blessings of Paradise are exclusively for those who believed and obeyed. There are no exceptions and no second chances at that point."
  },
  51: {
    "those who took this ˹faith of Islam˺ as mere amusement and play": "The disbelievers treated religion as a joke, something to mock or dismiss. They did not take the message seriously, finding entertainment in ridiculing faith and believers.",
    "and were deluded by ˹their˺ worldly life.\"": "They were completely absorbed in worldly life—its pleasures, distractions, and pursuits—to the point that they forgot about the Hereafter. The world deceived them into thinking it would last forever or that it was all that mattered.",
    "˹Allah will say,˺ \"Today We will ignore them just as they ignored the coming of this Day of theirs": "Allah will treat them as they treated His message. They ignored the Day of Judgment, so now Allah ignores their pleas. This is perfect justice—the response matches the crime. They had their chance and wasted it.",
    "and for rejecting Our revelations.\"": "They deliberately rejected Allah's signs when they had the opportunity to believe. Now, in their moment of need, they find that the door of mercy they once closed is now closed to them permanently."
  },
  52: {
    "We have certainly brought them a Book": "Allah affirms that He has sent down the Quran to humanity. It is not a human invention but a divine gift sent for their benefit.",
    "which We explained with knowledge—": "This Book is detailed and explained with perfect divine knowledge. Every verse, every word, every ruling is based on Allah's complete knowledge of what is best for humanity. The Quran covers theology, law, ethics, history, and guidance for every aspect of life—all explained with divine wisdom.",
    "a guide and mercy for those who believe.": "For those who accept it with faith, the Quran serves as guidance—showing them the right path in every matter—and as mercy—protecting them from harm in this life and the next. Note that this benefit is conditional on belief. Those who reject it deprive themselves of its guidance and mercy."
  },
  53: {
    "Do they only await the fulfilment ˹of its warning˺?": "Are the disbelievers waiting until the Day of Judgment and the punishments described in the Quran actually happen? Are they waiting for the warnings to become reality before they believe? By then, it will be too late.",
    "The Day it will be fulfilled, those who ignored it before will say, \"The messengers of our Lord certainly came with the truth.": "When that Day comes and they see everything the Quran warned about coming true, those who previously ignored and mocked the message will finally admit that the messengers spoke the truth. But this admission comes at the worst possible time—when it can no longer benefit them.",
    "Are there any intercessors who can plead on our behalf?": "In their desperation, they will look for someone to intercede for them, to speak on their behalf and save them from punishment. But intercession on that Day is only by Allah's permission and only for those He approves—not for those who died as disbelievers.",
    "Or can we be sent back so we may do ˹good,˺ unlike what we used to do?\"": "They will wish for a second chance, to return to the world and live differently. But this request will be denied. The time for action was in the worldly life; the Hereafter is only for recompense. Allah says elsewhere in the Quran that even if they were sent back, they would return to their old ways (6:28).",
    "They will have certainly ruined themselves,": "They have destroyed themselves through their own choices. No one forced them to disbelieve; they chose to ignore the guidance that was clearly presented to them.",
    "and whatever ˹gods˺ they fabricated will fail them.": "All the false gods, idols, ideologies, or beings they worshipped besides Allah will abandon them and be of no use. These fabricated deities have no power to help anyone, especially on that Day."
  },
  54: {
    "Indeed your Lord is Allah Who created the heavens and the earth in six Days,": "Allah introduces Himself as the Creator of the entire universe—the heavens and the earth and everything in between. He created all of this in six days. These \"days\" are according to Allah's measure, which is different from our 24-hour days. The point is that creation was deliberate and systematic, not random or accidental.",
    "then established Himself on the Throne.": "After creating the universe, Allah rose over His Throne (Al-Arsh) in a manner befitting His majesty. We affirm this as Allah described it without asking \"how\" or comparing it to creation. The Throne is the greatest of Allah's creations, and His establishing upon it indicates His sovereignty and authority over all creation.",
    "He makes the day and night overlap in rapid succession.": "Allah controls the cycle of day and night—one constantly following the other in perfect order. This continuous cycle is a sign of Allah's power and a mercy for creation, providing time for work and rest.",
    "He created the sun, the moon, and the stars—all subjected by His command.": "The celestial bodies—the sun that gives light and heat, the moon that marks months, and the stars that guide travelers—all operate according to Allah's command. They have no will of their own but are completely obedient to their Creator.",
    "The creation and the command belong to Him ˹alone˺.": "Allah is both the Creator of everything and the One who commands everything. He made it all, and He rules it all. No one shares in His creation, and no one shares in His authority.",
    "Blessed is Allah—Lord of all worlds!": "Allah is full of blessing (barakah), the source of all good, and the Lord and Master of all that exists—humans, jinn, angels, animals, plants, and everything in every realm of existence."
  },
  55: {
    "Call upon your Lord humbly and secretly.": "Allah teaches us how to make dua (supplication). We should call upon Him with humility, recognizing our need and His greatness. We should also pray privately and quietly, not making a show of our worship. Secret worship is more sincere and farther from showing off. The Prophet (peace be upon him) would often make dua quietly, moving only his lips.",
    "Surely He does not like the transgressors.": "Allah does not like those who transgress in their supplication—this includes those who pray loudly to show off, those who ask for inappropriate things (like asking for harm upon innocent people), and those who are insincere in their worship. Proper etiquette in dua is essential."
  },
  56: {
    "Do not spread corruption in the land after it has been set in order.": "Allah commands us not to cause corruption on earth after He has established order through His creation, His laws, and His messengers. Corruption includes sin, injustice, environmental destruction, moral decay, and anything that disrupts the good order Allah intended. This is a comprehensive command for Muslims to be forces of good, not harm.",
    "And call upon Him with hope and fear.": "When making dua, we should have both hope (that Allah will answer) and fear (of His punishment and our own shortcomings). A believer lives between hope and fear—hoping for Allah's mercy while fearing His justice. Neither extreme is healthy: too much hope leads to complacency, while too much fear leads to despair.",
    "Indeed, Allah's mercy is always close to the good-doers.": "Allah's mercy is near to those who do good (muhsineen). If you want Allah's mercy, be a person of ihsan—excellence in worship and in dealings with others. The Prophet (peace be upon him) defined ihsan as worshipping Allah as if you see Him, and if you cannot achieve that, knowing that He sees you."
  },
  57: {
    "He is the One Who sends the winds ushering in His mercy.": "Allah sends winds as good news, announcing the coming of rain, which is a mercy from Him. The winds carry moisture and bring relief to dry lands and thirsty creatures.",
    "When they bear heavy clouds, We drive them to a lifeless land": "When the winds have gathered heavy, rain-filled clouds, Allah directs them to lands that are dead—dry, barren, and seemingly without life.",
    "and then cause rain to fall, producing every type of fruit.": "Allah sends down rain, and suddenly the dead land comes alive. Plants grow, fruits appear, and life flourishes where there was nothing before. This is a clear demonstration of Allah's power.",
    "Similarly, We will bring the dead to life,": "This is the key lesson: just as Allah brings dead land to life with rain, He will bring dead human beings back to life on the Day of Resurrection. The same power that transforms a barren desert into a lush garden can easily raise the dead from their graves.",
    "so perhaps you will be mindful.": "Allah presents this example so that people will reflect and remember. The natural world is full of signs pointing to resurrection, but only those who pay attention will benefit from them."
  },
  58: {
    "The fertile land produces abundantly by the Will of its Lord,": "Good, fertile soil receives rain and produces abundant crops and fruits by Allah's permission. This represents the believer whose heart is pure and receptive—when guidance comes, it takes root and produces beautiful results: faith, good deeds, and positive influence on others.",
    "whereas the infertile land hardly produces anything.": "Bad, infertile soil receives the same rain but produces little or nothing useful—perhaps only weeds and thorns. This represents the disbeliever or the hard-hearted person. The same guidance comes to them, but their hearts reject it or produce only corruption.",
    "This is how We vary ˹Our˺ lessons to those who are thankful.": "Allah presents lessons in different ways—through stories, parables, logical arguments, and natural phenomena—so that people can understand and be grateful. Those who are thankful will recognize these lessons and benefit from them."
  },
  59: {
    "Indeed, We sent Noah to his people.": "Allah begins a series of stories about prophets, starting with Noah (peace be upon him). Noah was sent to his people who had fallen into idol worship after earlier generations had been monotheists.",
    "He said, \"O my people! Worship Allah—you have no other god except Him.": "Noah's message was simple and clear: worship Allah alone. This is the core message of every prophet. There is no deity worthy of worship except Allah. All other objects of worship are false and cannot help or harm anyone.",
    "I truly fear for you the torment of a tremendous Day.\"": "Noah warned his people out of genuine concern for them. He feared that if they continued in their disbelief, they would face terrible punishment. A true caller to Allah warns people because he cares about them, not to feel superior to them."
  },
  60: {
    "But the chiefs of his people said, \"We surely see that you are clearly misguided.\"": "The leaders and elite of Noah's people responded with arrogance and insults. Instead of considering his message, they dismissed him as misguided and lost. This is a common pattern: those in power often reject truth because it threatens their status and lifestyle."
  },
  61: {
    "He replied, \"O my people! I am not misguided!": "Noah calmly and firmly rejected their accusation. He did not respond with anger or counter-insults but simply stated the truth about himself.",
    "But I am a messenger from the Lord of all worlds,": "He clarified his position: he was not speaking from his own desires or confusion but was an authorized messenger from Allah, the Lord of everything that exists. His message carried divine authority."
  },
  62: {
    "conveying to you my Lord's messages": "His job was to deliver Allah's messages faithfully. He was a transmitter of divine guidance, not an inventor of religious ideas.",
    "and giving you ˹sincere˺ advice.": "Beyond just delivering the message, Noah genuinely advised his people for their own benefit. He was their well-wisher, not their enemy.",
    "And I know from Allah what you do not know.": "Through revelation, Noah had knowledge that his people lacked. He knew about the coming punishment, the truth of the Hereafter, and realities they could not see. This is why following prophets is so important—they have access to knowledge we cannot obtain on our own."
  },
  63: {
    "Do you find it astonishing that a reminder should come to you from your Lord through one of your own,": "Noah addressed their possible objection: Why would Allah send a human messenger? But this is actually a mercy—Allah sent someone they could relate to, who spoke their language and understood their situation. A human messenger is more accessible than an angel.",
    "warning you, so you may beware": "The purpose of the warning was to make them cautious and help them avoid punishment. Warnings are acts of mercy, not cruelty.",
    "and perhaps be shown mercy?\"": "The ultimate goal was that they might receive Allah's mercy. Everything about the prophetic mission is aimed at bringing people to Allah's mercy and saving them from His punishment."
  },
  64: {
    "But they rejected him,": "Despite Noah's patient preaching for 950 years, the majority of his people rejected his message. Only a small number believed.",
    "so We saved him and those with him in the Ark,": "Allah commanded Noah to build an ark, and when the flood came, Noah and the believers were saved on the ship. This is one of the most famous events in religious history, mentioned in the Quran, the Bible, and traditions around the world.",
    "and drowned those who rejected Our signs.": "The great flood destroyed all the disbelievers. The same water that saved the believers became the means of destruction for the rejecters.",
    "They were certainly a blind people.": "Allah describes them as blind—not physically, but spiritually. They could not see the truth even when it was right in front of them. Their hearts were sealed because of their persistent rejection."
  },
  65: {
    "And to the people of 'Âd We sent their brother Hûd.": "After Noah's people, another civilization arose and fell into misguidance: the people of 'Âd. They lived in the Arabian Peninsula and were known for their strength, tall stature, and impressive buildings. Allah sent Hûd (peace be upon him), who was from among them, as their messenger.",
    "He said, \"O my people! Worship Allah—you have no other god except Him.": "Hûd's message was identical to Noah's: pure monotheism. All prophets came with the same fundamental message.",
    "Will you not then fear Him?\"": "Hûd appealed to their sense of taqwa (God-consciousness). Will you not be aware of Allah and fear displeasing Him?"
  },
  66: {
    "The disbelieving chiefs of his people responded, \"We surely see you as a fool,": "The elite of 'Âd responded even more harshly than Noah's people. They called Hûd foolish and lacking intelligence. When people cannot refute a message, they often attack the messenger personally.",
    "and we certainly think you are a liar.\"": "They also accused him of lying. This is ironic because prophets are known for their truthfulness. The Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) was called \"Al-Amin\" (the Trustworthy) even before his prophethood."
  },
  67: {
    "Hûd replied, \"O my people! I am no fool!": "Hûd responded with dignity, denying their false accusations calmly and clearly.",
    "But I am a messenger from the Lord of all worlds,": "Like Noah, he affirmed his prophetic mission. His authority came from Allah, not from himself."
  },
  68: {
    "conveying to you my Lord's messages.": "His duty was to transmit Allah's message accurately and completely.",
    "And I am your sincere advisor.": "He emphasized his sincerity and trustworthiness. He was not seeking personal gain but genuinely wanted what was best for his people."
  },
  69: {
    "Do you find it astonishing that a reminder should come to you from your Lord through one of your own so he may warn you?": "Hûd used similar reasoning to Noah—questioning why they found it strange that Allah would send a human messenger.",
    "Remember that He made you successors after the people of Noah": "Hûd reminded them of their history. They inherited the earth after Noah's people were destroyed. They should learn from that history, not repeat the same mistakes.",
    "and increased you greatly in stature.": "Allah had blessed 'Âd with physical strength and tall bodies. They were known for their impressive physiques. But these blessings should lead to gratitude, not arrogance.",
    "So remember Allah's favours, so you may be successful.\"": "Hûd urged them to remember and be grateful for Allah's blessings. Gratitude leads to success; ingratitude leads to destruction."
  },
  70: {
    "They said, \"Have you come to us so that we would worship Allah alone and abandon what our forefathers used to worship?": "They understood Hûd's message perfectly but rejected it because it meant abandoning their ancestral traditions. Blind following of forefathers, even when they were wrong, is a recurring obstacle to truth throughout history.",
    "Then bring us what you threaten us with, if what you say is true!\"": "They arrogantly challenged Hûd to bring the punishment he warned about. This kind of challenge—demanding immediate punishment as proof—shows extreme foolishness and arrogance."
  },
  71: {
    "He said, \"You will certainly be subjected to your Lord's torment and wrath.": "Hûd warned them that punishment was coming. They had sealed their fate through their persistent rejection.",
    "Do you dispute with me regarding the so-called gods which you and your forefathers have made up—a practice Allah has never authorized?": "Hûd pointed out the absurdity of their position. They were arguing in defense of gods that they and their ancestors invented—names without any reality, beings without any power, worshipped without any authority from Allah.",
    "Then wait! I too am waiting with you.\"": "Hûd told them to wait for the outcome. He was confident in Allah's promise and ready to see whose position would be vindicated."
  },
  72: {
    "So We saved him and those with him by Our mercy": "Allah saved Hûd and the believers through His mercy. Salvation is always a mercy from Allah, not something we earn or deserve.",
    "and uprooted those who denied Our signs.": "Allah completely destroyed the people of 'Âd. They were annihilated by a fierce wind that lasted for days, leaving nothing but ruins. Their impressive buildings and strong bodies could not save them from Allah's punishment.",
    "They were not believers.": "The fundamental reason for their destruction was their refusal to believe. Despite clear signs and a sincere messenger, they chose to reject truth."
  },
  73: {
    "And to the people of Thamûd We sent their brother Ṣâliḥ.": "After 'Âd came Thamûd, another powerful civilization in Arabia. They were skilled architects who carved homes into mountains. Allah sent Ṣâliḥ (peace be upon him) as their prophet.",
    "He said, \"O my people! Worship Allah—you have no other god except Him.": "The same core message of monotheism.",
    "A clear proof has come to you from your Lord: this is Allah's she-camel as a sign to you.": "Ṣâliḥ came with a miraculous sign—a special she-camel that Allah brought forth from a rock. This was undeniable proof of his prophethood.",
    "So leave her to graze ˹freely˺ on Allah's land and do not harm her,": "The condition was simple: leave the camel alone, let her graze freely. She would share the water supply with them on alternate days. This was a test of their obedience.",
    "or else you will be overcome by a painful punishment.\"": "Ṣâliḥ warned them clearly of the consequence of harming the camel. The warning was explicit and left no room for confusion."
  },
  74: {
    "Remember when He made you successors after 'Âd": "Like Hûd did with 'Âd, Ṣâliḥ reminded Thamûd of their history. They succeeded the destroyed 'Âd and should learn from their fate.",
    "and established you in the land—˹and˺ you built palaces on its plains and carved homes into mountains.": "Allah blessed Thamûd with skills and resources to build impressive structures—both on flat land and carved into rocky mountains. Their architectural achievements were renowned.",
    "So remember Allah's favours,": "These blessings should lead to gratitude and obedience, not pride and disobedience.",
    "and do not go about spreading corruption in the land.\"": "Ṣâliḥ commanded them to avoid corruption—injustice, immorality, and destruction. Power and skill should be used for good, not evil."
  },
  75: {
    "The arrogant chiefs of his people asked the lowly who believed among them, \"Are you certain that Ṣâliḥ has been sent by his Lord?\"": "The arrogant elite questioned the humble believers mockingly. They looked down on those who believed because they were poor or of lower social status. This class division is a recurring theme—the powerful often reject truth while the humble accept it.",
    "They replied, \"We certainly believe in what he has been sent with.\"": "The believers responded with confidence and clarity. They affirmed their faith without wavering, regardless of the social pressure from the elite."
  },
  76: {
    "The arrogant said, \"We surely reject what you believe in.\"": "The arrogant elite declared their disbelief openly. They were proud of their rejection, seeing it as a mark of their superiority. This is the pinnacle of arrogance—boasting about disbelief."
  },
  77: {
    "Then they killed the she-camel—defying their Lord's command—": "In an act of extreme arrogance and rebellion, they killed the miraculous she-camel. This was not an accident but a deliberate violation of Allah's clear command through His prophet.",
    "and challenged ˹Ṣâliḥ˺, \"Bring us what you threaten us with, if you are ˹truly˺ one of the messengers.\"": "After killing the camel, they arrogantly challenged Ṣâliḥ to bring the punishment he warned about. Like 'Âd before them, they demanded proof through punishment. They would soon regret this challenge."
  },
  78: {
    "Then an ˹overwhelming˺ earthquake struck them,": "Allah answered their challenge with a devastating earthquake (or a blast—some scholars say both). The same mountains they carved and trusted in became their graves.",
    "and they fell lifeless in their homes.": "They were found dead in their homes, collapsed and motionless. Their impressive rock-carved dwellings could not protect them from Allah's punishment. The very homes they were so proud of became their tombs."
  },
  79: {
    "So he turned away from them, saying, \"O my people!": "After the punishment fell, Ṣâliḥ turned away from the destroyed remains of his people and spoke these words of sorrow and closure.",
    "Surely I conveyed to you my Lord's message and gave you ˹sincere˺ advice,": "Ṣâliḥ affirmed that he had fulfilled his duty. He delivered the message faithfully and advised them sincerely. He had done everything a prophet should do.",
    "but you do not like ˹sincere˺ advisors.\"": "The problem was not with the message or the messenger—it was with the listeners. They did not want sincere advice because it challenged their desires and lifestyle. This is a profound observation: people often reject good advice not because it is wrong but because they do not want to hear the truth."
  },
  80: {
    "And ˹remember˺ when Lot scolded ˹the men of˺ his people": "Allah reminds us of the story of Prophet Lot (Lut), who was sent to the people of Sodom. Lot was the nephew of Prophet Ibrahim and was tasked with guiding a particularly corrupt society. He stood firmly against their wrongdoing and warned them persistently, fulfilling his duty as a prophet despite their resistance.",
    "˹saying,˺ \"Do you commit a shameful deed": "Lot confronted his people about their immoral behavior, calling it what it truly was—a shameful and obscene act. He did not sugarcoat their sin or remain silent out of fear. This teaches us that speaking the truth about wrongdoing is part of sincere advice, even when it is uncomfortable.",
    "that no man has ever done before?": "This sin was unprecedented in human history. Before the people of Sodom, no community had engaged in this particular form of immorality on such a widespread scale. This emphasizes the severity of their transgression—they were pioneers in a great evil, and being the first to normalize a sin carries an even heavier burden."
  },
  81: {
    "You lust after men instead of women!": "Lot clearly identified their sin—they had abandoned the natural way that Allah created, which is the relationship between men and women within marriage. Instead, they pursued unnatural desires with other men. This was a corruption of the natural order (fitrah) that Allah established in creation.",
    "You are certainly transgressors.": "Lot declared them as people who had exceeded all limits and boundaries set by Allah. The word 'transgressors' indicates those who go beyond what is permissible into what is forbidden. Their sin was not just a personal failing but a collective rebellion against divine guidance and natural law."
  },
  82: {
    "But his people's only response was to say,": "Instead of reflecting on Lot's warning or feeling any shame for their actions, his people responded with arrogance and hostility. This shows how deeply corrupted their hearts had become—they had no interest in reform or repentance.",
    "\"Expel them from your land!": "They demanded that Lot and those who believed with him be driven out of the city. This is a common tactic of those who persist in wrongdoing—rather than change themselves, they try to silence or remove those who remind them of the truth. They wanted to eliminate the voice of guidance rather than eliminate the sin.",
    "They are a people who wish to remain chaste!\"": "Remarkably, they mocked Lot and the believers for wanting to stay pure and avoid immorality. They used purity as an insult! This shows the complete inversion of values in their society—what should be praised (chastity) became a reason for ridicule, and what should be condemned (immorality) became normalized. When a society reaches this point, its destruction becomes imminent."
  },
  83: {
    "So We saved him and his family": "When the time for punishment arrived, Allah rescued Prophet Lot and the believers who were with him. Allah's mercy always provides a way out for those who remain faithful. Angels came to Lot, instructed him to leave the city at night, and warned him not to look back.",
    "except his wife, who was one of the doomed.": "Lot's own wife was not saved because she secretly sympathized with the disbelievers and supported their way of life. Despite being in the household of a prophet, she did not truly believe. This teaches us that family ties alone cannot save a person—each individual is responsible for their own faith. Being related to righteous people does not guarantee salvation if one's own heart is corrupt."
  },
  84: {
    "We poured upon them a rain ˹of brimstone˺.": "Allah sent upon them a devastating punishment—stones of baked clay rained down from the sky, destroying everything. The land was also turned upside down. This was not ordinary rain but a rain of destruction, specifically designed for their annihilation. The punishment fit the crime—they had turned nature upside down with their behavior, so their land was literally turned upside down.",
    "See what was the end of the wicked!": "Allah invites us to reflect on the fate of those who persisted in sin and rejected guidance. Their cities were completely destroyed, and the area where they lived (near the Dead Sea) remains a barren wasteland to this day—a lasting sign for those who reflect. This is a warning for all generations that wickedness, especially when it becomes normalized in a society, leads to destruction."
  },
  85: {
    "And to the people of Midian We sent their brother Shu'aib.": "Allah sent Prophet Shu'aib to the people of Midian, a region in northwest Arabia. He is called their 'brother' because he was from among them—he knew their language, culture, and struggles. This made his message more relatable and left them with no excuse to reject him as an outsider.",
    "He said, \"O my people! Worship Allah—you have no other god except Him.": "Like all prophets, Shu'aib began with the most fundamental message: worship Allah alone. This is the foundation of faith. Without correct belief in God, no other aspect of life can be truly righteous. The people of Midian had strayed from monotheism and needed to return to the worship of the One True God.",
    "A clear proof has already come to you from your Lord.": "Shu'aib reminded them that Allah had sent them clear evidence and signs to prove the truth of his message. They could not claim ignorance—the truth had been made manifest to them through miracles, logical arguments, and the messenger himself.",
    "So give just measure and weight,": "Beyond spiritual corruption, the people of Midian were notorious for economic fraud. They would cheat in business transactions by using dishonest scales—giving less when selling and taking more when buying. Shu'aib commanded them to be fair and honest in all their dealings. Islam connects worship with ethics; one cannot claim to worship Allah while cheating others.",
    "do not defraud people of their property,": "This is a broader command against all forms of theft, deception, and taking what belongs to others unjustly. Whether through cheating, manipulation, or outright stealing, depriving people of their rightful property is a major sin. The Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) said that a person who cheats is not from us, emphasizing how seriously Islam takes honesty in transactions.",
    "nor spread corruption in the land after it has been set in order.": "Allah created the earth in a balanced and orderly state. When people engage in injustice, fraud, and immorality, they corrupt this balance. The people of Midian were spreading corruption through their dishonest practices, disrupting the social and economic harmony that should exist among people.",
    "This is for your own good, if you are ˹truly˺ believers.": "Shu'aib reminded them that following Allah's commands benefits them, not Allah. Honesty leads to trust, stable societies, and Allah's blessings. True believers understand that divine guidance is a mercy, not a burden."
  },
  86: {
    "And do not lie in ambush on every road—": "The disbelievers among Midian would position themselves on roads and pathways to intercept travelers. This may have been literal highway robbery, or it could also refer to them setting up 'checkpoints' to intimidate those who wanted to follow Shu'aib's message.",
    "threatening and hindering those who believe in Allah from His Path": "They actively tried to prevent people from accepting faith. When someone showed interest in following Shu'aib, these people would threaten them, mock them, or pressure them to stay away from the truth. Blocking others from guidance is a severe sin because it harms not just oneself but prevents others from being saved.",
    "and striving to make it ˹appear˺ crooked.": "They tried to make the straight path of Allah appear crooked, confusing, or unappealing. They spread lies about Shu'aib and his message, twisted his words, and presented falsehood as truth. This is the tactic of every corrupt group—to make evil seem good and good seem evil.",
    "Remember when you were few, then He increased you in number.": "Shu'aib reminded them of Allah's blessings upon them. At one time, they were a small, weak community. Allah blessed them with growth, prosperity, and strength. Instead of being grateful and obedient, they used these blessings to spread corruption and oppose the truth.",
    "And consider the fate of the corruptors!": "He warned them to look at history and see what happened to previous nations who spread corruption—they were all destroyed. This should serve as a lesson and deterrent. Those who corrupt society never escape Allah's justice."
  },
  87: {
    "If some of you do believe in what I have been sent with while others do not,": "Shu'aib acknowledged that his people were divided—some believed in his message while others rejected it. This division is natural; not everyone accepts guidance, and that is their choice to make.",
    "then be patient until Allah judges between us.": "Shu'aib advised patience and trust in Allah. He did not call for violence or forced conversion. Instead, he left the final judgment to Allah. This teaches us that our job is to convey the truth; the outcome is in Allah's hands.",
    "He is the Best of Judges.": "Allah's judgment is perfect, fair, and final. Unlike human judges who may be biased, mistaken, or corrupt, Allah knows everything and judges with absolute justice. Believers can take comfort in this—no injustice will go unaddressed."
  },
  88: {
    "The arrogant chiefs of his people threatened,": "It was the elite and powerful leaders who led the opposition to Shu'aib. Arrogance blinded them from accepting the truth because accepting it would mean admitting they were wrong and giving up their corrupt ways of making money. Power and wealth often become barriers to guidance.",
    "\"O Shu'aib! We will certainly expel you and your fellow believers from our land,": "Just like Lot's people, these leaders threatened exile and banishment. They had the power to kick out anyone they disagreed with. This is a form of persecution that many prophets and their followers faced—being forced to leave their homes simply for believing in Allah.",
    "unless you return to our faith.\"": "They gave Shu'aib an ultimatum: abandon your message and come back to our false beliefs, or be expelled. This shows that the real issue was not about Shu'aib personally but about the message he brought. They wanted him to compromise his faith.",
    "He replied, \"Even if we hate it?": "Shu'aib asked a powerful rhetorical question: Would you force us back to falsehood even though we despise it? This shows that faith is a matter of the heart—it cannot be forced or compelled. A person cannot truly 'return' to disbelief once they have tasted the sweetness of faith."
  },
  89: {
    "We would surely be fabricating a lie against Allah if we were to return to your faith": "Shu'aib explained that going back to false beliefs after Allah has shown him the truth would be the greatest lie against Allah. To reject truth after recognizing it is to deny what Allah has made clear. This would be a betrayal of the knowledge Allah has given.",
    "after Allah has saved us from it.": "Allah had rescued Shu'aib and the believers from the darkness of ignorance and misguidance. Returning to falsehood after being saved from it would be ingratitude of the highest order—like being pulled from a burning building and then walking back into the fire.",
    "It does not befit us to return to it unless it is the Will of Allah, our Lord.": "Shu'aib acknowledged that he has no power except what Allah wills. While he has no intention of ever returning to falsehood, he recognizes that all matters are ultimately in Allah's hands. This is humility before Allah—never claiming absolute certainty about oneself but relying on Allah's guidance and protection.",
    "Our Lord has encompassed everything in ˹His˺ knowledge.": "Allah's knowledge is complete and perfect. He knows the hearts of the believers, the schemes of the disbelievers, and everything that will happen. This gives the believers confidence—they are not alone; Allah sees and knows all.",
    "In Allah we trust.": "This is a declaration of complete reliance on Allah. Despite the threats of expulsion and persecution, Shu'aib and the believers placed their trust in Allah alone. This is the foundation of a believer's strength—knowing that Allah is the best Protector and Helper.",
    "Our Lord! Judge between us and our people with truth.": "Shu'aib turned to Allah in supplication, asking Him to settle the matter between the believers and disbelievers with His just judgment. He did not seek revenge but asked for truth and justice to prevail.",
    "You are the best of those who judge.": "Allah's judgment is superior to any human judgment. He knows all the facts, motives, and hidden realities. His decision is final and perfect, and the believers accept it completely."
  },
  90: {
    "The disbelieving chiefs of his people threatened,": "The arrogant leaders continued their campaign against Shu'aib by trying to intimidate anyone who might consider following him. They used their social status and influence to discourage people from accepting the truth.",
    "\"If you follow Shu'aib, you will surely be losers!\"": "They threatened social and economic ruin to anyone who believed. They defined 'success' by worldly standards—wealth, status, and fitting in with the powerful. In their eyes, following the truth would lead to loss of these things. How ironic that they called the believers 'losers' when they themselves were about to lose everything in this world and the next."
  },
  91: {
    "Then an ˹overwhelming˺ earthquake struck them": "Allah's punishment came in the form of a devastating earthquake that shook their entire region. In other places in the Quran, their punishment is also described as a mighty blast from the sky. The combination of these catastrophes completely annihilated them.",
    "and they fell lifeless in their homes.": "The earthquake was so sudden and severe that they died right where they were, in their own houses. They had no chance to escape or prepare. Just moments before, they were going about their daily lives, feeling secure in their power and wealth. In an instant, everything was over."
  },
  92: {
    "Those who rejected Shu'aib were ˹wiped out˺ as if they had never lived there.": "Their destruction was so complete that it was as if they had never existed. All their buildings, their wealth, their power—gone without a trace. This is a powerful reminder of how temporary worldly things are. What seems permanent can vanish in a moment.",
    "Those who rejected Shu'aib were the true losers.": "Allah turns their own words against them. They had called the believers 'losers,' but in reality, they were the ones who lost everything—their lives, their wealth, and their chance at eternal salvation. The real loss is not losing worldly things but losing one's soul and afterlife."
  },
  93: {
    "He turned away from them, saying,": "After the destruction, Shu'aib turned away from their ruined dwellings. Though he was a compassionate prophet, he could not save those who refused to save themselves.",
    "\"O my people! Indeed, I have delivered to you the messages of my Lord": "Shu'aib affirmed that he had fulfilled his duty completely. He had conveyed every message Allah sent, holding nothing back. A prophet's job is to deliver the message clearly—he cannot force people to accept it.",
    "and gave you ˹sincere˺ advice.": "He had not only delivered the message but had done so with genuine concern for their wellbeing. His advice was sincere, coming from a heart that wanted them to be saved. He was not seeking personal gain or power—he truly wanted good for them.",
    "How can I then grieve for those who chose to disbelieve?\"": "This is not a statement of cold indifference but rather an acknowledgment of a painful reality. Shu'aib had done everything possible, and they had rejected it all. Grief is natural, but prolonged grief over those who consciously chose destruction despite every warning is not appropriate. They made their choice with full knowledge of the consequences."
  },
  94: {
    "Whenever We sent a prophet to a society,": "Allah explains His consistent pattern throughout history. Whenever He sent a messenger to guide a people, there was also a test that accompanied the message.",
    "We afflicted its ˹disbelieving˺ people with suffering and adversity,": "Allah tested them with hardships—poverty, illness, loss, and other difficulties. These hardships came upon those who initially disbelieved and rejected the prophet's message.",
    "so perhaps they would be humbled.": "The purpose of these trials was not cruelty but mercy. Hardship has a way of softening hard hearts and making people turn to Allah. When a person is comfortable and has everything, they often forget Allah. But when difficulties strike, they may remember their need for Him. Allah sends trials as a wake-up call, giving people a chance to humble themselves and return to Him before it's too late."
  },
  95: {
    "Then We changed their adversity to prosperity until they flourished": "When the hardship did not reform them, Allah tried another approach—He blessed them with ease, wealth, and good times. Their population grew, their wealth increased, and life became comfortable.",
    "and argued ˹falsely˺, \"Our forefathers ˹too˺ had been visited by adversity and prosperity.\"": "Instead of recognizing Allah's blessings and being grateful, they dismissed both the hardships and ease as mere coincidence or natural cycles. They said their ancestors also went through ups and downs, so there was nothing special about it—no divine message, no test, no need to change. This is a dangerous form of denial: dismissing Allah's signs as random occurrences.",
    "So We seized them by surprise, while they were unaware.": "Because they failed to heed the warnings in hardship and failed to show gratitude in ease, Allah's punishment came suddenly when they least expected it. They were living their lives, feeling secure, when destruction overtook them. This is the fate of those who ignore all of Allah's reminders."
  },
  96: {
    "Had the people of those societies been faithful and mindful ˹of Allah˺,": "Allah presents a conditional statement showing the alternative path these destroyed nations could have taken. If only they had believed in Allah and His messengers, and if they had lived with consciousness of Allah (taqwa), their fate would have been completely different.",
    "We would have overwhelmed them with blessings from heaven and earth.": "Allah would have opened the doors of provision from every direction—rain from the skies, crops from the earth, peace, security, and abundance in all things. This is not just material blessings but also spiritual tranquility and harmony. Faith brings comprehensive blessings in both worlds.",
    "But they disbelieved, so We seized them for what they used to commit.": "Instead of choosing faith, they chose denial. And because of their persistent disbelief and sins, Allah's punishment became justified. They earned their destruction through their own choices and actions. Allah did not wrong them; they wronged themselves."
  },
  97: {
    "Did the people of those societies feel secure that Our punishment would not come upon them by night while they were asleep?": "Allah asks a rhetorical question to make us reflect. Did those destroyed nations think they were safe from Allah's punishment coming at night while they slept peacefully in their beds? Sleep is a time of complete vulnerability—a person has no awareness or ability to defend themselves. Yet they lived as if no punishment could ever reach them."
  },
  98: {
    "Or did they feel secure that Our punishment would not come upon them by day while they were at play?": "Or did they think punishment could not come during the day when they were busy with entertainment and amusement? The contrast between night (when asleep) and day (when playing) covers all times. The point is that punishment can come at any moment—when you're resting or when you're enjoying yourself. No time is 'safe' for those who defy Allah."
  },
  99: {
    "Did they feel secure against Allah's planning?": "Allah's 'planning' here refers to His way of dealing with those who persist in sin—He may give them respite, let them enjoy for a while, and then seize them when they least expect it. Did they think they could outsmart Allah or that they were beyond His reach?",
    "None would feel secure from Allah's planning except the losers.": "Only the truly foolish and spiritually bankrupt feel completely safe from Allah's consequences. A believer lives with hope in Allah's mercy but also with awareness of His power. Feeling completely immune from divine accountability is itself a sign of being lost. The wise person maintains a balance between hope and fear."
  },
  100: {
    "Is it not clear to those who take over the land after ˹the destruction of˺ its former residents": "Allah addresses those who came after the destroyed nations and inherited their lands, homes, and resources. They walked among the ruins, saw the evidence of past civilizations that were wiped out, and took over what remained.",
    "that—if We will—We can punish them ˹too˺ for their sins": "Allah warns the inheritors that they are not immune. If they commit similar sins and reject guidance just like the previous nations, Allah can punish them in the same way. The ruins they walk past are a warning, not just historical curiosities.",
    "and seal their hearts so they will not hear ˹the truth˺?": "When a person persistently rejects truth and ignores warning after warning, Allah may seal their heart as a consequence of their own choices. This sealing means they lose the ability to truly hear and understand guidance. The warning is clear: don't let your heart become so hardened that you can no longer recognize truth when it comes to you."
  },
  101: {
    "We have narrated to you ˹O Prophet˺ some of the stories of those societies.": "Allah tells Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) that these stories of destroyed nations are being related to him for important purposes—to strengthen his heart, warn his people, and provide lessons for all of humanity until the Day of Judgment.",
    "Surely, their messengers came to them with clear proofs,": "Every destroyed nation received a messenger who brought clear evidence of the truth. They were not left without guidance. The signs, miracles, and logical arguments presented to them were sufficient to convince any sincere seeker of truth.",
    "but still they would not believe in what they had already denied.": "Despite all the clear proofs, they refused to believe. Their rejection was not due to lack of evidence but due to stubborn denial. Once they had initially rejected the truth, they became locked into that denial and would not reconsider, no matter how many more proofs came.",
    "This is how Allah seals the hearts of the disbelievers.": "Allah seals hearts as a consequence, not as an arbitrary act. When someone repeatedly rejects truth, ignores warnings, and chooses denial over faith, Allah confirms them in their state. It's like a path that gets blocked because you refused to walk on it so many times—eventually, you lose the ability to even see it. This is a warning to take truth seriously when it comes, before the heart becomes sealed."
  },
  102: {
    "We did not find most of them true to their covenant.": "Allah states that most of these destroyed peoples did not honor their commitments. The covenant refers to the natural agreement between Creator and creation—that humans would worship Allah alone and follow His guidance. It also includes the specific promises they made to their prophets. They broke their word repeatedly.",
    "Rather, We found most of them truly rebellious.": "The majority were not just neutral or indifferent—they were actively rebellious, deliberately going against what they knew to be right. This is worse than ignorance; it is knowing the truth and choosing to defy it anyway. The word 'rebellious' indicates open defiance and corruption, not mere weakness or occasional sin. This was their consistent character, and it led to their destruction."
  },
  138: {
    "We brought the Children of Israel across the sea": "Allah reminds us of the great miracle He performed for the Children of Israel—parting the sea so they could escape from Pharaoh's tyranny. This was one of the most extraordinary miracles in history, demonstrating Allah's absolute power and His special favor upon them. They had just witnessed the destruction of the mightiest army of that time.",
    "and they came upon a people devoted to idols.": "Shortly after this miraculous deliverance, they encountered a tribe who were deeply committed to idol worship. These people spent their time devoted to statues, bowing to them and seeking blessings from objects that had no power whatsoever. This was the first exposure of the Israelites to such open polytheism after leaving Egypt.",
    "They demanded, \"O Moses! Make for us a god like their gods.\"": "Astonishingly, instead of feeling grateful to Allah and recognizing the foolishness of idol worship, the Israelites asked Moses to create an idol for them too! They had just been saved by the One True God, yet they wanted to imitate the pagans. This shows how deeply the culture of Egypt had influenced them—they had lived among idol worshippers for so long that they thought this was normal religious practice.",
    "He replied, \"Indeed, you are a people acting ignorantly!": "Moses responded with justified frustration. He called them ignorant because their request showed a complete lack of understanding of who Allah is. How could they ask for a man-made idol after witnessing Allah's power? True knowledge of Allah makes idol worship unthinkable. Their request was not just wrong—it was foolish and showed they had learned nothing from their miraculous rescue."
  },
  139: {
    "What they follow is certainly doomed to destruction": "Moses explained that the idol-worshipping people they admired were heading toward complete ruin. Their entire way of life, their beliefs, and their practices were destined to be destroyed. There is no future in worshipping false gods—only destruction in this world and the next.",
    "and their deeds are in vain.": "All the worship, sacrifices, and devotion these idol worshippers offered to their statues were completely worthless. Their deeds earned them nothing because they were directed at objects that could neither help nor harm anyone. This is the reality of all worship directed to other than Allah—it is nullified and brings no reward."
  },
  140: {
    "He added, \"Shall I seek for you a god other than Allah,": "Moses asked them a rhetorical question to make them realize the absurdity of their request. Why would he, a prophet of Allah, search for another god when he has direct connection to the One True God? This question was meant to shake them into awareness.",
    "while He has honoured you above the others?\"": "Moses reminded them of their special status. Allah had chosen them above all the nations of their time, blessed them with prophets, saved them from slavery, and shown them miracle after miracle. After all these favors, how could they even think of seeking another god? Ingratitude of this magnitude was almost incomprehensible. When Allah blesses someone, the appropriate response is increased devotion, not seeking alternatives."
  },
  142: {
    "We appointed for Moses thirty nights then added another ten—": "Allah summoned Moses for a special meeting at Mount Sinai. Initially, the appointment was for thirty nights of spiritual preparation, worship, and fasting. Then Allah extended it by ten more nights, completing a total of forty nights.",
    "completing his Lord's term of forty nights.": "The forty nights were necessary for Moses to be spiritually prepared to receive the Torah and to have the honor of speaking directly with Allah. This extended period of devotion, seclusion, and worship purified Moses and prepared him for the tremendous responsibility of receiving divine scripture. The number forty appears in many significant events in Islamic tradition—it represents a period of completion and preparation.",
    "Moses commanded his brother Aaron, \"Take my place among my people,": "Before leaving, Moses appointed his brother Aaron (Harun) as his deputy to lead and look after the Children of Israel in his absence. Aaron was also a prophet and was qualified to maintain order and continue guiding the people. This shows the importance of proper succession and leadership—Moses did not leave his people without guidance.",
    "do what is right,": "Moses instructed Aaron to maintain righteousness and justice among the people. A leader's primary duty is to establish what is good and correct. Aaron was to continue teaching them, resolving their disputes fairly, and keeping them on the path of obedience to Allah.",
    "and do not follow the way of the corruptors.\"": "Moses specifically warned Aaron not to give in to those who spread corruption. This warning proved to be prophetic, as some among the people would soon cause great corruption by creating the golden calf. Moses knew his people's weaknesses and wanted Aaron to stand firm against any deviation, no matter the pressure."
  },
  143: {
    "When Moses came at the appointed time and his Lord spoke to him,": "Moses arrived at Mount Sinai after completing his preparation, and Allah honored him by speaking to him directly without any intermediary. This was one of Moses' unique distinctions—he is known as 'Kalimullah' (the one to whom Allah spoke directly). This direct communication was an immense honor that few have ever received.",
    "he asked, \"My Lord! Reveal Yourself to me so I may see You.\"": "Overwhelmed by the experience of hearing Allah's speech, Moses' longing to be even closer to his Lord intensified. He made a bold request—to see Allah with his own eyes. This request came from pure love and desire for nearness to Allah, not from doubt or disrespect. Moses wanted the ultimate experience of witnessing his Creator.",
    "Allah answered, \"You cannot see Me!": "Allah informed Moses that seeing Him is not possible in this worldly life. Human beings in their current physical form cannot withstand the sight of Allah's majesty. This is not a deficiency in Allah but a limitation of human capacity in this world. The vision of Allah is reserved for the believers in Paradise, where they will be given the ability to experience this greatest of blessings.",
    "But look at the mountain. If it remains firm in its place, only then will you see Me.\"": "Allah gave Moses a demonstration to help him understand why seeing Allah is impossible in this life. He directed Moses to watch the mountain—a massive, solid structure made of rock. Allah would manifest some of His light to the mountain, and if the mountain could remain standing, then perhaps Moses could bear the sight.",
    "When his Lord appeared to the mountain, He levelled it to dust": "When Allah manifested just a fraction of His light to the mountain, the entire mountain—millions of tons of solid rock—was instantly crushed to fine dust. It could not withstand even a glimpse of Allah's majesty. This demonstrated to Moses that if a mighty mountain was obliterated, how could a fragile human being endure such a sight?",
    "and Moses collapsed unconscious.": "Even witnessing this event from a distance caused Moses to lose consciousness. The sheer power and awe of what he witnessed was too much for his human body to handle. This shows the immense gap between the Creator and creation—we cannot fully comprehend Allah's greatness while in this limited worldly state.",
    "When he recovered, he cried, \"Glory be to You!": "Upon regaining consciousness, Moses immediately glorified Allah, declaring Him free from any imperfection or limitation. He realized that Allah is far beyond what any creation can perceive or comprehend. This was an expression of awe, humility, and recognition of Allah's transcendence.",
    "I turn to You in repentance": "Moses repented for his request, not because asking was sinful, but out of humility and recognition that he had asked for something beyond human capacity in this world. He acknowledged his human limitation and submitted to Allah's wisdom.",
    "and I am the first of the believers.\"": "Moses declared himself the first among his people to believe fully and submit to Allah's decree. After this experience, his faith was even more solidified. He accepted that some things about Allah are beyond human comprehension and experience in this life, and that is part of faith."
  },
  144: {
    "Allah said, \"O Moses! I have ˹already˺ elevated you above all others by My messages and speech.": "Allah consoled Moses by reminding him of the tremendous honors he had already received. He was chosen to be a prophet, given divine messages, and granted the unique privilege of speaking directly with Allah. These honors placed him above all other people of his time. While seeing Allah was not possible, Moses had blessings that no one else had.",
    "So hold firmly to what I have given you": "Allah instructed Moses to focus on the blessings and responsibilities he had been given rather than longing for what was not decreed. He should hold tightly to the divine message, implement it in his life, and convey it to his people. This is a lesson for all of us—appreciate and utilize what Allah has given you instead of being preoccupied with what you don't have.",
    "and be grateful.\"": "Gratitude is the appropriate response to Allah's favors. Moses was reminded to be thankful for his unique status as a prophet and a direct recipient of Allah's speech. When we recognize and appreciate Allah's blessings, He increases them. Ingratitude, on the other hand, leads to loss of blessings."
  },
  145: {
    "We wrote for him on the Tablets ˹the fundamentals˺ of everything; commandments and explanations of all things.": "Allah gave Moses the Torah inscribed on tablets. These tablets contained comprehensive guidance—laws, commandments, moral teachings, and explanations covering all aspects of life that the Children of Israel needed. Nothing essential was left out. This was a complete code of life for them to follow.",
    "˹We commanded,˺ \"Hold to this firmly": "Allah instructed Moses to grasp these teachings with strength and determination, not weakly or half-heartedly. Divine guidance requires serious commitment. One cannot casually follow Allah's commands when convenient and ignore them when difficult. True faith means holding firmly to guidance in all circumstances.",
    "and ask your people to take the best of it.": "Moses was to instruct his people to follow the best interpretations and applications of the divine law. When given options, they should choose the higher path. This also means acting on the clear commands while being careful with the more difficult matters. The goal is always excellence in obedience, not looking for the easiest way out.",
    "I will soon show ˹all of˺ you the home of the rebellious.\"": "Allah warned that He would show them the destroyed remains of previous rebellious nations—their ruined cities and civilizations. These ruins serve as physical evidence of what happens to those who defy Allah's commands. Seeing these remnants would reinforce the lesson that rebellion against Allah leads to destruction."
  },
  146: {
    "I will turn away from My signs those who act unjustly with arrogance in the land.": "Allah declares that the arrogant will be deprived of understanding His signs. When a person is filled with pride and thinks they are above following guidance, Allah removes the ability to benefit from divine signs. Arrogance is a barrier between a person and truth. This is not Allah being unjust—it is the natural consequence of their own attitude.",
    "And even if they were to see every sign, they still would not believe in them.": "Their arrogance is so severe that even if they witnessed countless miracles and clear proofs, they would still refuse to believe. The problem is not lack of evidence but a corrupted heart that refuses to accept truth. Many disbelievers throughout history saw undeniable miracles yet rejected them because their pride would not allow them to submit.",
    "If they see the Right Path, they will not take it.": "Even when the path of truth and righteousness is made crystal clear to them, they will deliberately avoid it. They recognize it but choose not to follow it because following it would require humility and change—things their arrogance cannot accept.",
    "But if they see a crooked path, they will follow it.": "In contrast, when they see a path of misguidance and deviation, they eagerly embrace it. This shows their complete moral inversion—what should be avoided becomes attractive to them, and what should be embraced becomes repulsive. Their hearts have become so corrupted that they are drawn to falsehood.",
    "This is because they denied Our signs and were heedless of them.": "Allah explains the cause of their condition. It started with denial and heedlessness. They rejected Allah's signs when they first came and paid no attention to the warnings. Over time, this denial and negligence hardened their hearts until they reached this pitiable state where truth and falsehood are reversed in their perception."
  },
  147: {
    "The deeds of those who deny Our signs and the meeting ˹with Allah˺ in the Hereafter will be in vain.": "Those who reject Allah's signs and deny that they will meet Him for judgment will find that all their worldly deeds are worthless. Without faith, even seemingly good actions have no value in the sight of Allah because they were not done for His sake. Denial of the Hereafter removes the foundation upon which good deeds are built.",
    "Will they be rewarded except for what they have done?\"": "This rhetorical question emphasizes that people will receive exactly what they earned. Those who invested in disbelief and denial will receive the fruits of that investment—nothing. Allah's judgment is perfectly just; everyone gets precisely what they deserve based on their choices and actions."
  },
  148: {
    "In the absence of Moses, his people made from their ˹golden˺ jewellery an idol of a calf": "While Moses was away receiving the Torah, a man named Samiri collected gold jewelry from the people and crafted it into the shape of a calf. The people had brought this gold with them from Egypt. Instead of being patient and waiting for their prophet to return, they fell into a grave sin.",
    "that made a lowing sound.": "Through some trickery, Samiri made the calf produce a sound like a real cow. This impressed the ignorant among the people and made them think there was something special or divine about this statue. In reality, it was just a trick—there was nothing miraculous about a hollow metal statue making noise.",
    "Did they not see that it could neither speak to them nor guide them to the ˹Right˺ Path?": "Allah points out the obvious absurdity of their worship. This calf could not speak meaningful words, respond to prayers, or provide any guidance. It was a lifeless object. How could rational people worship something so clearly powerless? True deity would communicate, guide, and respond—none of which this calf could do.",
    "Still they took it as a god and were wrongdoers.": "Despite the obvious impotence of the idol, they worshipped it anyway. This was a tremendous act of injustice—injustice to Allah by associating partners with Him, and injustice to themselves by abandoning the truth for falsehood. Their action was not a mistake but a deliberate choice to worship a creation instead of the Creator."
  },
  149: {
    "Later, when they were filled with remorse": "After the initial excitement faded and reality set in, many of them began to feel deep regret for what they had done. The Arabic expression indicates that they felt trapped by their own hands—they had done something terrible and now had to face the consequences.",
    "and realized they had gone astray,": "They recognized that they had deviated from the straight path. This self-awareness is the first step toward repentance. Acknowledging one's sin honestly is necessary before forgiveness can be sought. They could no longer deny or justify their actions.",
    "they cried, \"If our Lord does not have mercy on us and forgive us, we will certainly be losers.\"": "They turned to Allah in desperation, knowing that only His mercy could save them. They acknowledged that without divine forgiveness, they would be among those who lose everything. This shows that even after major sins, the door of repentance remains open. Their regret was genuine, and they sought Allah's mercy."
  },
  150: {
    "Upon Moses' return to his people, ˹totally˺ furious and sorrowful,": "When Moses came back from Mount Sinai, he was filled with two emotions: intense anger at their betrayal and deep sorrow at what they had done to themselves. Allah had already informed him about the calf incident, so he returned knowing what had happened. His anger was righteous anger—fury at the violation of Allah's commands.",
    "he said, \"What an evil thing you committed in my absence!": "Moses immediately confronted them about their terrible deed. He expressed shock and disappointment that they could not even remain faithful for the short time he was away. This was not just any sin—it was the worst possible sin: worshipping other than Allah.",
    "Did you want to hasten your Lord's torment?\"": "Moses asked them if they were deliberately trying to bring Allah's punishment upon themselves faster. Their impatience had led them to this sin. Instead of waiting patiently for Moses and trusting in Allah's plan, they rushed into misguidance.",
    "Then he threw down the Tablets": "In his intense anger, Moses threw down the sacred Tablets containing Allah's law. Some scholars say the tablets broke, while others say Allah protected them. Either way, this action shows the depth of Moses' distress. He had just received the greatest gift—divine scripture—and returned to find his people worshipping a cow.",
    "and grabbed his brother by the hair, dragging him closer.": "Moses turned to Aaron, whom he had left in charge, and grabbed him in anger. He pulled Aaron by his head, demanding an explanation for this failure. This was not abuse but the reaction of a leader devastated by the failure of his deputy and his people.",
    "Aaron pleaded, \"O son of my mother!": "Aaron addressed Moses in a tender way, reminding him of their close family bond through their mother. This emotional appeal was meant to calm Moses down and help him listen to the explanation. It was also a way of asking for gentleness between brothers.",
    "The people overpowered me and were about to kill me.": "Aaron explained that he was not complicit in the sin. The people had turned against him when he tried to stop them. They threatened his life, and he was powerless against the mob. He had done what he could but was ultimately overwhelmed by the corrupt majority.",
    "So do not ˹humiliate me and˺ make my enemies rejoice,": "Aaron asked Moses not to treat him harshly in front of everyone, as this would give satisfaction to those who opposed them both. Publicly humiliating Aaron would weaken their position and embolden the wrongdoers.",
    "nor count me among the wrongdoing people.\"": "Aaron firmly stated that he was not one of the transgressors. He had not participated in the calf worship and had tried to prevent it. He asked to be judged based on his actions, not the actions of those he could not control."
  },
  151: {
    "Moses prayed, \"My Lord! Forgive me and my brother!": "After understanding Aaron's situation, Moses turned to Allah in prayer. He asked forgiveness for himself—perhaps for his harsh initial reaction to Aaron—and for his brother, who had faced an impossible situation. This shows the prophetic character: quick to seek forgiveness and to make peace.",
    "And admit us into Your mercy.": "Moses asked Allah to envelop them both in His divine mercy. Being under Allah's mercy means protection, guidance, and success in both worlds. Moses recognized that without Allah's mercy, even prophets cannot succeed.",
    "You are the Most Merciful of the merciful.\"": "Moses appealed to Allah's supreme attribute of mercy. Among all who show mercy, Allah's mercy is the greatest and most encompassing. By invoking this attribute, Moses expressed hope and confidence that Allah would forgive and protect them."
  },
  152: {
    "Those who worshipped the calf will certainly be afflicted with Allah's wrath": "Allah decreed that those who participated in the calf worship would face His anger. This is not a small matter—Allah's wrath is the most severe consequence a person can face. Idol worship is the one sin that Allah does not forgive if a person dies without repenting from it.",
    "as well as disgrace in the life of this world.": "In addition to divine wrath, they would suffer humiliation in their worldly lives. This disgrace manifested in various ways throughout their history. This worldly punishment was a precursor to what awaited them in the Hereafter if they did not sincerely repent.",
    "This is how We reward those who invent falsehood.": "Allah states that this is the standard recompense for those who fabricate lies against Him—inventing gods, creating false religions, or attributing partners to Allah. Such people will face consequences in both worlds. The creation of the calf and claiming it as a god was a fabrication of the worst kind."
  },
  153: {
    "But those who commit evil, then repent and become ˹true˺ believers,": "Allah opens the door of hope for those who sinned. Despite the severity of their transgression, those who genuinely repented and reaffirmed their faith were given another chance. Repentance must be sincere and followed by genuine faith—not just words but a transformation of the heart.",
    "your Lord will certainly be All-Forgiving, Most-Merciful.": "Allah promises that He will forgive those who truly repent. His forgiveness is complete, and His mercy is abundant. This verse brings tremendous hope—no matter how grave the sin, sincere repentance can erase it. Allah wants people to return to Him and gives them multiple opportunities to do so."
  },
  154: {
    "When Moses' anger subsided, he took up the Tablets": "After his initial rage passed, Moses composed himself and picked up the Tablets. A wise person does not act in the heat of anger but waits until they have calmed down. Moses' anger was justified, but handling sacred scripture and making important decisions required a clear mind.",
    "whose text contained guidance and mercy for those who stand in awe of their Lord.": "The Tablets contained everything the people needed—guidance to show them the right path and mercy to bring them blessings and forgiveness. However, these benefits were specifically for those who had reverence and awe of Allah. Those who approach divine guidance with humility and fear of Allah are the ones who truly benefit from it. The proud and dismissive cannot access the mercy contained in scripture."
  },
  155: {
    "Moses chose seventy men from among his people for Our appointment": "Moses selected seventy men from the Children of Israel to accompany him to Mount Sinai for a special appointment with Allah. These were presumably the best among them, chosen to witness something significant and bring the message back to their people.",
    "and, when they were seized by an earthquake,": "During this meeting, an earthquake struck and killed or incapacitated the seventy men. This may have been a punishment for the collective sins of the community, including the calf worship, or a test to see how Moses would respond.",
    "he cried, \"My Lord! Had You willed, You could have destroyed them long ago, and me as well.": "Moses turned to Allah with a heartfelt plea. He acknowledged that Allah could have destroyed all of them—including Moses himself—much earlier if He had wanted. This statement recognizes Allah's complete power and also subtly appeals to His mercy for having spared them thus far.",
    "Will You destroy us for what the foolish among us have done?": "Moses argued that it would not be appropriate for the innocent to be destroyed for the sins of the foolish. He was interceding on behalf of his people, trying to protect them from collective punishment. This is what a true leader does—stands between their people and harm, pleading for mercy.",
    "This is only a test from You—": "Moses recognized that the challenges they faced were divine tests. Allah tests people to distinguish the faithful from the unfaithful, the patient from the impatient. Moses understood that tests are part of life and are meant to purify and elevate those who pass them.",
    "by which You allow whoever You will to stray and guide whoever You will.": "Moses acknowledged that guidance and misguidance are ultimately in Allah's hands. He does not force anyone but gives guidance to those who seek it sincerely and allows those who turn away to go astray. This is a statement of accepting Allah's divine wisdom in all matters.",
    "You are our Guardian. So forgive us and have mercy on us.": "Moses declared that Allah is their protector and caretaker. As their Guardian, He would surely show them mercy. Moses asked for forgiveness of their sins and for divine mercy to cover their shortcomings.",
    "You are the best forgiver.": "Allah's forgiveness is unlike any other. When He forgives, He forgives completely—not holding grudges or reminding of past sins. He is the best at forgiving because His forgiveness is perfect, complete, and coupled with love for those who repent."
  },
  156: {
    "Ordain for us what is good in this life and the next.": "Moses continued his supplication by asking for good in both worlds. He did not ask only for worldly success or only for the Hereafter—he asked for both, as a believer should. This teaches us to balance our prayers, seeking Allah's blessings in all aspects of life.",
    "Indeed, we have turned to You ˹in repentance˺.\"": "Moses affirmed that they had repented sincerely and turned back to Allah. Repentance is not just feeling sorry but actively turning away from sin and returning to obedience. Moses spoke on behalf of his people, confirming their collective return to Allah.",
    "Allah replied, \"I will inflict My torment on whoever I will.": "Allah first affirmed His complete authority over punishment. He punishes according to His wisdom—those who deserve it based on their choices and actions. This reminds us that we cannot escape accountability; divine justice is certain.",
    "But My mercy encompasses everything.": "Then Allah gave one of the most hopeful statements in the entire Quran. His mercy is vast enough to encompass all of creation. Nothing is outside the reach of Allah's mercy. This mercy is fundamental to His nature and exceeds His wrath, as the Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) taught us.",
    "I will ordain mercy for those who shun evil,": "Allah specified who will receive His special mercy: those who have taqwa (consciousness of Allah) and avoid evil. This mercy is not random but is particularly reserved for those who make an effort to stay away from sin out of love and fear of Allah.",
    "pay alms-tax,": "Those who pay their obligatory charity (zakah) are among those who will receive divine mercy. Zakah purifies wealth and the heart, showing that a person values Allah's pleasure over material accumulation. It demonstrates care for others and obedience to Allah's commands.",
    "and believe in Our revelations.": "Finally, those who believe in Allah's signs and scriptures—accepting them, following them, and living by them—are promised Allah's mercy. Belief is not passive but active acceptance that transforms how one lives. Those who meet these three criteria will find that Allah's encompassing mercy is specifically ordained for them."
  },
  157: {
    "˹They are˺ the ones who follow the Messenger, the unlettered Prophet,": "This verse describes those who will receive Allah's special mercy—they are the followers of Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him). He is called 'unlettered' because he could not read or write, which itself is a miracle. The Quran, the most eloquent book ever, came through a man who never received formal education. This proves the divine origin of his message—no human could produce such a masterpiece without Allah's direct revelation.",
    "whose description they find in their Torah and the Gospel.": "The coming of Prophet Muhammad was foretold in the previous scriptures given to Moses and Jesus. The People of the Book (Jews and Christians) had descriptions of the final prophet in their texts—his characteristics, his mission, and even his location. Many of the companions who converted from Judaism and Christianity, like Abdullah ibn Salam, recognized him immediately from these descriptions. This prophecy removes any excuse for rejection.",
    "He commands them to do good and forbids them from evil,": "The Prophet's mission includes establishing moral order. He teaches people what is right and warns them against what is wrong. This is the foundation of a healthy society—promoting virtue and preventing vice. Every aspect of his teachings aims to elevate human character and create a just community.",
    "permits for them what is lawful and forbids to them what is impure,": "The Prophet clarifies what is permissible (halal) and what is forbidden (haram). Everything pure and beneficial is permitted, while everything harmful and impure is prohibited. This guidance covers food, drink, transactions, relationships, and all aspects of life. Allah's law is not arbitrary—it is designed for human wellbeing.",
    "and relieves them from their burdens and the shackles that bound them.": "Previous nations, particularly the Children of Israel, had been given very strict laws as a consequence of their disobedience. The Prophet Muhammad's message brought ease and lifted many of these heavy burdens. Islam is designed to be practical and manageable for all people in all times. The Prophet said, 'I was sent with the easy, pure monotheism.' This is a mercy from Allah.",
    "˹Only˺ those who believe in him, honour and support him, and follow the light sent down to him will be successful.": "True success belongs to those who fulfill four conditions: believing in the Prophet, honoring and respecting him, supporting his mission, and following the Quran (the light). These are not separate paths but interconnected requirements. One cannot claim to believe while refusing to follow. Those who meet these conditions achieve success in both worlds."
  },
  158: {
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"O humanity! I am Allah's Messenger to you all.": "The Prophet is commanded to declare his universal mission. Unlike previous prophets who were sent to specific nations, Muhammad is sent to all of humanity—Arabs and non-Arabs, East and West, present and future generations. No one is excluded from this message. This is what makes Islam the final and complete religion.",
    "To Him ˹alone˺ belongs the kingdom of the heavens and the earth.": "Allah owns and controls everything in existence. The heavens, the earth, and everything between them belong to Him. He is the true King with absolute authority. When we understand this, we realize that only He deserves our worship and obedience.",
    "There is no god ˹worthy of worship˺ except Him.": "This is the core declaration of faith (tawheed). No deity, idol, person, or concept deserves worship except Allah alone. All false gods are powerless inventions. This simple yet profound statement is the foundation of Islam and the key to Paradise.",
    "He gives life and causes death.\"": "Allah alone controls the most fundamental realities of existence—life and death. No one can give life to the dead or prevent death when its time comes. Medical science, technology, and human effort are all subject to His will. Recognizing this should humble us and direct our worship to Him alone.",
    "So believe in Allah and His Messenger, the unlettered Prophet, who believes in Allah and His revelations.": "Based on the truths just stated, Allah commands belief in Him and in His Messenger. The Prophet himself is a believer—he practices what he preaches and is the first to submit to Allah's commands. His sincerity and devotion are models for all believers.",
    "And follow him, so you may be ˹rightly˺ guided.": "Belief alone is not enough; it must be accompanied by following the Prophet's example. The Quran provides the message, and the Prophet's life shows how to implement it. Following him leads to guidance in all matters—spiritual, social, and personal. Without following him, one cannot claim to be truly guided."
  },
  159: {
    "There are some among the people of Moses who guide with the truth": "Allah acknowledges that not all of the Children of Israel went astray. There has always been a righteous group among them who upheld truth and guided others to it. This balanced perspective prevents unfair generalizations—while many transgressed, some remained faithful to their covenant with Allah.",
    "and establish justice accordingly.": "These righteous ones not only knew the truth but also implemented it fairly. They judged between people with justice, without favoritism or corruption. Knowledge of truth must be paired with just action—this is the mark of true believers in any community."
  },
  160: {
    "We divided them into twelve tribes—each as a community.": "Allah organized the Children of Israel into twelve distinct tribes, each descended from one of the sons of Prophet Yaqub (Jacob). This division helped maintain order and identity among this large nation. Each tribe had its own leaders and responsibilities.",
    "And We revealed to Moses, when his people asked for water, \"Strike the rock with your staff.\"": "When the Israelites were in the desert and desperately needed water, Allah instructed Moses to strike a rock with his staff. This was a test of faith—logically, hitting a rock does not produce water. But Moses obeyed without hesitation, trusting in Allah's command.",
    "Then twelve springs gushed out. Each tribe knew its drinking place.": "Miraculously, twelve separate springs burst from the rock—one for each tribe. This organized distribution prevented conflict and showed Allah's precise care for their needs. Every tribe had its designated source, ensuring fairness and order. This miracle demonstrated that Allah can provide from the most unlikely sources.",
    "We shaded them with clouds": "In the harsh desert sun, Allah provided them with miraculous cloud cover that followed them and shaded them from the heat. This was not natural desert weather but a direct blessing from Allah, making their journey bearable.",
    "and sent down to them manna and quails,": "Allah provided them with ready-made food in the wilderness. Manna was a sweet, nutritious substance that appeared each morning, and quails (birds) came to them for meat. They did not need to farm, hunt, or work for this food—it came directly from Allah.",
    "˹saying,˺ \"Eat from the good things We have provided for you.\"": "Allah invited them to enjoy these pure blessings. These provisions were not just for survival but were good, wholesome, and enjoyable. Allah is generous with His servants and wants them to appreciate His gifts.",
    "They ˹certainly˺ did not wrong Us, but wronged themselves.": "Despite all these blessings, many of them were ungrateful and disobedient. But their ingratitude did not harm Allah in any way—Allah is self-sufficient and needs nothing from His creation. Their sins only harmed themselves, depriving them of even greater blessings and earning them punishment."
  },
  161: {
    "And ˹remember˺ when it was said to them, \"Enter this city ˹of Jerusalem˺": "After their time in the wilderness, Allah commanded them to enter the blessed city of Jerusalem. This was supposed to be their promised land, a reward for their patience and struggles.",
    "and eat from wherever you please.": "Once inside, they were free to enjoy the city's abundance without restriction. Allah's provisions awaited them—they just needed to enter and partake. This was a generous offer requiring minimal effort on their part.",
    "Say, 'Absolve us,'": "They were instructed to enter with a word of repentance and humility on their lips. Saying 'Absolve us' (Hittah) meant asking Allah to remove their sins. It was a simple condition—acknowledge your shortcomings and seek forgiveness.",
    "and enter the gate with humility.": "They were to enter the city bowing in humility and gratitude, not with arrogance or pride. Physical humility reflects inner humility. After all Allah had done for them, entering with bowed heads was the least they could do.",
    "We will forgive your sins,": "Allah promised complete forgiveness if they fulfilled these simple conditions. Their past mistakes would be erased, and they would enter the blessed city with a clean slate. What a generous offer!",
    "˹and˺ We will multiply the reward for the good-doers.\"": "Beyond forgiveness, those who excelled in goodness would receive multiplied rewards. Allah not only forgives but increases the rewards of those who go beyond the minimum requirements. His generosity knows no bounds."
  },
  162: {
    "But the wrongdoers among them changed the words they were commanded to say.": "Instead of saying 'Absolve us' as commanded, the rebellious among them mocked the instruction and said something completely different. Some narrations say they changed the word to something insulting or trivial. This was deliberate disobedience and mockery of divine commands—a serious transgression.",
    "So We sent down a punishment from the heavens upon them for their wrongdoing.": "Their mockery and disobedience brought divine punishment upon them. A plague or other calamity descended from the sky, afflicting those who had transgressed. This shows that playing with Allah's commands and mocking His instructions has severe consequences. Simple obedience would have brought forgiveness; arrogant mockery brought destruction."
  },
  163: {
    "Ask them ˹O Prophet˺ about ˹the people of˺ the town which was by the sea,": "Allah instructs the Prophet to remind the Jews of his time about a story well-known to them—the story of a coastal town whose inhabitants violated the Sabbath. This was a test of their knowledge and a reminder of what happens to those who disobey.",
    "who broke the Sabbath.": "The people of this town violated the sanctity of Saturday (the Sabbath), which was a day they were forbidden from working, including fishing. This was a sacred day of rest and worship that they were required to observe.",
    "During the Sabbath, ˹abundant˺ fish would come to them clearly visible,": "Allah tested them by making fish appear in abundance every Saturday. The fish would swim near the surface, easily visible and catchable. It was as if the fish were presenting themselves to be caught.",
    "but on other days the fish were never seen.": "On the other six days when fishing was permitted, the fish would disappear. This created a powerful temptation—the fish were plentiful precisely when they were forbidden to catch them, and absent when they were allowed to fish.",
    "In this way We tested them for their rebelliousness.": "This was a deliberate test from Allah to see if they would obey His command even when obedience was difficult and temptation was strong. Their previous rebelliousness had earned them this trial. Tests reveal true character—would they prioritize Allah's command over their desires?"
  },
  164: {
    "When some of ˹the righteous among˺ them questioned ˹their fellow Sabbath-keepers˺, \"Why do you ˹bother to˺ warn those ˹Sabbath-breakers˺ who will either be destroyed or severely punished by Allah?\"": "The community was divided into three groups: those who broke the Sabbath, those who warned against it, and those who remained silent. The silent group asked the warners why they bothered advising people who seemed determined to disobey. They felt it was pointless since punishment was inevitable.",
    "They replied, \"Just to be free from your Lord's blame,": "The warners explained their motivation. They continued advising not because they expected success, but to fulfill their duty to Allah. On the Day of Judgment, they could say they tried. Enjoining good and forbidding evil is an obligation regardless of whether people listen. We are responsible for our effort, not the outcome.",
    "and so perhaps they may abstain.\"": "The second reason was hope. Perhaps someone would listen and change. You never know whose heart might be touched by sincere advice. Even if most reject, saving even one person is worth the effort. This teaches us to never give up on advising others, as long as there is even a small chance of benefit."
  },
  165: {
    "When they ignored the warning they were given,": "The transgressors paid no attention to the sincere advice they received. They continued violating the Sabbath, deaf to all warnings. When people reach this stage of stubbornness, they have sealed their own fate.",
    "We rescued those who used to warn against evil": "Allah saved the group that fulfilled their duty of forbidding evil. Their sincere efforts to guide others earned them divine protection. This shows the importance of speaking up against wrongdoing—it may save you even if it doesn't save others.",
    "and overtook the wrongdoers with a dreadful punishment for their rebelliousness.": "Those who violated the Sabbath were seized by a severe punishment. Their deliberate, persistent disobedience brought upon them exactly what they had been warned about. The silent group's fate is not explicitly mentioned, which has led scholars to different conclusions about them."
  },
  166: {
    "But when they stubbornly persisted in violation,": "Their disobedience was not a one-time slip but a persistent, arrogant rebellion. They deliberately continued sinning despite knowing it was wrong and despite being warned repeatedly. This stubborn persistence in sin is far worse than momentary weakness.",
    "We said to them, \"Be disgraced apes!\"": "Allah transformed them into apes as a humiliating punishment. They had behaved like animals—driven purely by desire without moral restraint—so they were made to physically become what they had spiritually become. This was a visible, public disgrace that served as a lesson for others. According to scholars, these transformed people did not reproduce; they died out within a few days, leaving behind only the lesson of their punishment."
  },
  167: {
    "And ˹remember, O Prophet,˺ when your Lord declared that He would send against them others who would make them suffer terribly until the Day of Judgment.": "Allah decreed that because of their persistent disobedience, the Children of Israel would be subjected to oppression and persecution by various nations throughout history until the Day of Judgment. This has manifested throughout history as different empires and peoples have dominated and persecuted them. This is a consequence of breaking their covenant with Allah.",
    "Indeed, your Lord is swift in punishment,": "When Allah decides to punish, nothing can delay or prevent it. His punishment comes swiftly when decreed. This serves as a warning to all who think they can escape divine justice or that their sins will go unnoticed.",
    "but He is certainly All-Forgiving, Most Merciful.": "Yet despite His ability to punish swiftly, Allah remains ready to forgive those who repent. His mercy is always available to those who turn back to Him sincerely. This balance of justice and mercy is central to understanding Allah's nature—He punishes when necessary but prefers to forgive."
  },
  168: {
    "We dispersed them through the land in groups—": "Allah scattered the Children of Israel across different lands rather than keeping them unified in one place. This dispersion was a consequence of their disobedience. They lost their unity and homeland, becoming minorities in various nations.",
    "some were righteous, others were less so.": "Even in their dispersed state, they remained a mixed community. Some held firmly to righteousness and Allah's commands, while others fell short. This is true of any community—there are always different levels of faith and practice.",
    "We tested them with prosperity and adversity,": "Allah tested them with both good times and hardship. Some were blessed with wealth and comfort, while others faced poverty and difficulty. Both conditions are tests—prosperity tests gratitude, while adversity tests patience. Neither state is permanent or absolute.",
    "so perhaps they would return ˹to the Right Path˺.": "The purpose of these varying conditions was to bring them back to Allah. Hardship might humble them, and blessings might make them grateful. Allah uses different methods to guide people, always leaving the door of return open."
  },
  169: {
    "Then they were succeeded by other generations who inherited the Scripture.": "After the earlier generations, new generations came who received the Torah as their inheritance. They had access to divine guidance and knowledge of Allah's commands, but inheritance of scripture does not guarantee righteousness.",
    "They indulged in unlawful gains,": "Despite knowing better, they pursued forbidden wealth—through bribery, corruption, interest, and other prohibited means. They sold their principles for worldly profit. Knowledge without action is worthless; in fact, it increases accountability.",
    "claiming, \"We will be forgiven ˹after all˺.\"": "They justified their sins by presuming upon Allah's forgiveness. They assumed they could sin freely and still be forgiven because they were the 'chosen people' or because they had the scripture. This false sense of security led them deeper into sin.",
    "And if similar gain came their way, they would seize it.": "Their claim of seeking forgiveness was insincere because they would repeat the same sins whenever opportunity arose. True repentance involves intending not to repeat the sin. Their pattern of sinning, claiming forgiveness, and sinning again showed their repentance was just words.",
    "Was a covenant not taken from them in the Scripture that they would not say anything about Allah except the truth?": "Allah reminds them of their covenant to speak only truth about Him. Claiming guaranteed forgiveness while persisting in sin is a lie about Allah. He never promised unconditional forgiveness to those who deliberately continue sinning.",
    "And they were already well-versed in its teachings.": "They had studied their scripture and knew exactly what it said. Their sin was not from ignorance but from deliberate choice to ignore what they knew. This makes their transgression even more severe—they sinned despite having full knowledge.",
    "But the ˹eternal˺ Home of the Hereafter is far better for those mindful ˹of Allah˺.": "Allah contrasts their choice with wisdom. The temporary gains of this world cannot compare to the eternal blessings of the Hereafter. Those with taqwa (consciousness of Allah) sacrifice temporary pleasures for permanent rewards. This is the smart trade.",
    "Will you not then understand?": "Allah appeals to their reason. Any logical person would choose eternal reward over temporary gain. Their behavior defies basic wisdom. This question challenges us all to think carefully about our priorities."
  },
  170: {
    "As for those who firmly abide by the Scripture": "In contrast to the corrupt inheritors, there are those who hold tightly to divine guidance. They don't just possess the scripture; they live by it, following its commands and avoiding its prohibitions. Their grip on faith is firm, not casual.",
    "and establish prayer—": "Prayer is highlighted specifically because it is the foundation of practice. Those who maintain regular prayer demonstrate ongoing commitment to Allah. Establishing prayer means performing it properly, consistently, and with full presence of heart.",
    "surely We never discount the reward of those acting righteously.": "Allah gives a powerful guarantee: He never wastes the reward of those who do good. Every good deed is recorded and will be fully compensated. This assurance encourages believers to persist in righteousness, knowing that nothing is lost with Allah."
  },
  171: {
    "And ˹remember˺ when We raised the mountain over them as if it were a cloud": "Allah reminds of the dramatic scene when He lifted Mount Sinai and suspended it above the Children of Israel. The massive mountain hung over them like a canopy or a cloud, demonstrating Allah's absolute power and the seriousness of His covenant.",
    "and they thought it would fall on them.": "They were certain the mountain would crash down upon them. This terrifying display was meant to impress upon them the gravity of the commitment they were making. This was not a casual agreement but a solemn covenant with the Creator of the universe.",
    "˹We said,˺ \"Hold firmly to that ˹Scripture˺ which We have given you": "In that moment of awe and fear, Allah commanded them to take His guidance seriously. They were not to treat the Torah casually but to grasp it with strength and determination. Half-hearted commitment to divine guidance is insufficient.",
    "and observe its teachings so perhaps you will become mindful ˹of Allah˺.\"": "The purpose of holding firmly to scripture is to develop taqwa—consciousness and mindfulness of Allah. Scripture is not for academic study alone but for practical implementation that transforms the heart and creates awareness of Allah in every aspect of life."
  },
  172: {
    "And ˹remember˺ when your Lord brought forth from the loins of the children of Adam their descendants": "This verse describes a primordial covenant that occurred before we entered this world. Allah extracted all human souls from Adam and his descendants—every human who would ever exist—and gathered them together.",
    "and had them testify regarding themselves.": "Each soul was made to witness concerning itself. This was not forced testimony but a recognition of truth. Every soul, in its pure state before worldly influences, acknowledged the reality of its Creator.",
    "˹Allah asked,˺ \"Am I not your Lord?\"": "Allah posed the fundamental question directly to all of humanity. This question addresses the most basic truth of existence: the relationship between Creator and creation, between the Lord and those He created.",
    "They replied, \"Yes, You are! We testify.\"": "Every soul, including yours and mine, affirmed Allah's lordship. In that pure state, without worldly distractions and ego, the truth was obvious and undeniable. This is why belief in God feels natural—it's recognizing something we already knew.",
    "˹He cautioned,˺ \"Now you have no right to say on Judgment Day, 'We were not aware of this.'\"": "This covenant removes the excuse of ignorance. No one can claim on the Day of Judgment that they didn't know about Allah's existence or lordship. The knowledge is embedded in human nature (fitrah). Those who disbelieve are suppressing what they inherently know."
  },
  173: {
    "Nor say, 'It was our forefathers who had associated others ˹with Allah in worship˺": "Another invalid excuse is blaming ancestors. People might claim they only followed the religion of their parents and didn't know any better. But this covenant proves that knowledge of Allah's oneness is innate—cultural conditioning doesn't erase it.",
    "and we, as their descendants, followed in their footsteps.": "Following blindly what parents believed is not a valid defense. Each person has their own primordial covenant with Allah and their own responsibility to seek truth. Being born into a misguided family does not justify remaining in misguidance.",
    "Will you then destroy us for the falsehood they invented?'\"": "People might argue it's unfair to punish them for their ancestors' errors. But Allah clarifies that punishment is for their own choices, not their ancestors'. Each person has enough awareness to question, seek, and find truth—especially when messengers are sent to guide them."
  },
  174: {
    "This is how We make Our signs clear,": "Allah explains these truths in detail so that understanding is possible for those who sincerely seek it. The signs are made clear through revelation, through the natural world, and through human conscience. Allah leaves no room for genuine confusion.",
    "so perhaps they will return ˹to the Right Path˺.": "The purpose of clarity is to facilitate return to truth. By explaining the primordial covenant, Allah awakens something deep within us—a memory of when we knew Him without doubt. This should stir the heart to return to what it originally acknowledged."
  },
  175: {
    "And relate to them ˹O Prophet˺ the story of the one to whom We gave Our signs,": "Allah commands the Prophet to tell the story of a person who had been given divine knowledge and signs. This person had access to truth and understanding that most people lack—he was blessed with religious scholarship and awareness.",
    "but he abandoned them,": "Despite having this knowledge, he chose to strip himself of it. The Arabic word suggests peeling off like skin—he completely separated himself from the guidance he had been given. He traded divine truth for worldly gains.",
    "so Satan took hold of him,": "When he abandoned Allah's guidance, he didn't remain neutral—Satan immediately seized him. There is no middle ground in spiritual matters; if you're not moving toward Allah, Satan is pulling you toward destruction. The scholar's knowledge didn't protect him once he abandoned practice.",
    "and he became a deviant.": "He ended up among those who are lost and misguided. This is the tragic end of someone who had everything needed for success but chose to throw it away. Knowledge without sincerity and action leads to the worst kind of deviation."
  },
  176: {
    "If We had willed, We would have elevated him with Our signs,": "Allah could have raised this person to the highest ranks through the knowledge he was given. Divine knowledge is meant to elevate its possessor in both worlds. He had the potential for greatness but squandered it.",
    "but he clung to this life—following his evil desires.": "Instead of using knowledge to rise spiritually, he became attached to worldly pleasures and followed his base desires. He used his knowledge to pursue wealth, status, or pleasure rather than to please Allah. When knowledge serves ego instead of truth, it becomes a curse rather than a blessing.",
    "His example is that of a dog: if you chase it away, it pants, and if you leave it, it ˹still˺ pants.": "Allah gives a powerful, unflattering comparison. A dog pants whether you chase it or leave it alone—its condition doesn't change based on external circumstances. Similarly, this type of person remains in the same lowly state whether advised or left alone. They are stuck in their base condition, unable to rise above animalistic behavior.",
    "This is the example of the people who deny Our signs.": "This comparison applies to all who reject Allah's signs despite having access to knowledge. They remain in spiritual panting—restless, unfulfilled, chasing worldly things—regardless of whether they are warned or left alone.",
    "So narrate ˹to them˺ stories ˹of the past˺, so perhaps they will reflect.": "Allah instructs the Prophet to tell these stories because stories have power to penetrate hearts. People might not respond to direct commands, but stories can inspire reflection. Perhaps hearing about others' downfall will cause some to reconsider their own path."
  },
  177: {
    "What an evil example of those who denied Our signs!": "Allah expresses how terrible the state of these deniers is. Their comparison to a constantly panting dog is not flattery but an accurate description of their degraded spiritual condition. This should cause anyone with self-respect to avoid such a state.",
    "They ˹only˺ wronged their own souls.": "Their rejection and deviation didn't harm Allah or anyone else primarily—they harmed themselves. Every sin is ultimately self-harm. They deprived themselves of guidance, mercy, and eternal success. The consequences of their choices fall squarely on them."
  },
  178: {
    "Whoever Allah guides is truly guided.": "True guidance comes only from Allah. When Allah guides someone, they are genuinely on the right path—nothing can lead them astray. Human efforts, intelligence, and resources cannot produce guidance without Allah's will. This should make us constantly ask Allah for guidance.",
    "And whoever He leaves to stray, they are the ˹true˺ losers.": "Those whom Allah allows to go astray—because of their own choices and rejection of truth—are the real losers. They may seem successful by worldly standards, but they have lost the most valuable thing: their souls and their eternal future. No worldly gain can compensate for this loss."
  },
  179: {
    "Indeed, We have destined many jinn and humans for Hell.": "Allah states a sobering reality: many among both jinn and humans will end up in Hell. This is not arbitrary but based on their choices. Allah's knowledge encompasses who will choose disbelief, and their destination is known to Him.",
    "They have hearts they do not understand with,": "These destined-for-Hell creatures have hearts, but they don't use them for their intended purpose. The heart is meant to recognize truth, feel connected to Allah, and understand spiritual realities. But their hearts are blocked—they refuse to process truth even when it reaches them.",
    "eyes they do not see with,": "They have functional eyes but don't see the signs of Allah all around them. The universe is full of evidence pointing to the Creator, but they look without seeing. Physical sight without spiritual insight is blindness of the worst kind.",
    "and ears they do not hear with.": "They have ears but don't hear the message of truth. Prophets and believers call them to guidance, but the words don't penetrate. They hear sounds but not meaning; they listen but don't comprehend.",
    "They are like cattle.": "Allah compares them to livestock—animals that eat, drink, and exist without higher purpose. Cattle don't reflect on existence or seek meaning. These people, despite having superior faculties, function at the level of animals, concerned only with physical needs and desires.",
    "In fact, they are even less guided!": "Actually, cattle are better because they fulfill their purpose and don't have the capacity for higher understanding. But humans and jinn who waste their God-given faculties are worse than animals because they had the potential for so much more and squandered it.",
    "Such ˹people˺ are ˹entirely˺ heedless.": "Their fundamental problem is heedlessness—they are unaware, careless, and inattentive to what truly matters. They sleepwalk through life, missing the entire point of existence. This heedlessness is the root of their destruction."
  },
  180: {
    "Allah has the Most Beautiful Names.": "Allah possesses names that are perfect and beautiful in every way. Each name reflects an attribute of absolute perfection. These include Ar-Rahman (The Most Merciful), Al-Alim (The All-Knowing), Al-Qadeer (The All-Powerful), and many others. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said there are ninety-nine names, and whoever memorizes and understands them will enter Paradise.",
    "So call upon Him by them,": "We are encouraged to invoke Allah using His beautiful names, choosing names appropriate to our needs. When seeking mercy, call upon Ar-Rahman. When seeking knowledge, call upon Al-Alim. When seeking provision, call upon Ar-Razzaq. Using Allah's names in supplication shows knowledge of Him and brings us closer to Him.",
    "and keep away from those who abuse His Names.": "Some people distort Allah's names—denying them, misinterpreting them, comparing them to creation, or deriving names for false gods from them. We must avoid such people and their practices. Allah's names are sacred and must be treated with proper respect and understanding.",
    "They will be punished for what they used to do.": "Those who abuse Allah's names will face consequences for their transgression. Whether through denial, distortion, or disrespect, tampering with Allah's names is a serious sin that will be addressed on the Day of Judgment. Allah's names reflect His essence, and disrespecting them is disrespecting Him."
  },
  181: {
    "And among those We created is a group that guides with the truth": "Allah affirms that throughout human history, there has always been a community of righteous people who guide others to truth. These are the prophets, scholars, and sincere believers who hold fast to divine guidance and share it with others. Truth is their standard and their message. This gives hope that guidance is always accessible for those who seek it.",
    "and establishes justice accordingly.": "These righteous guides don't just teach truth—they implement it through just actions. They judge between people fairly, give everyone their rights, and create systems based on divine justice. Knowledge of truth must lead to just practice; otherwise, it remains incomplete."
  },
  182: {
    "As for those who deny Our signs,": "In contrast to the righteous, there are those who reject Allah's clear signs and revelations. Despite evidence all around them and within them, they choose to deny the truth.",
    "We will gradually draw them to destruction in ways they cannot comprehend.": "Allah's way with such people is subtle and terrifying. He doesn't always punish immediately; instead, He leads them gradually toward their doom through means they don't recognize. Often, this comes through increasing their blessings—more wealth, health, and success—which makes them more arrogant and further from repentance. They think they are being rewarded when actually they are being set up for a greater fall. This is called 'istidraj'—a gradual leading toward destruction."
  },
  183: {
    "I ˹only˺ delay their end for a while,": "Allah grants the disbelievers respite. He doesn't destroy them immediately but gives them time—time that they mistake for approval or escape from consequences. This delay is not weakness on Allah's part but part of His perfect plan. It gives them opportunity to repent while also completing the evidence against them.",
    "but My planning is flawless.": "Allah's plan is strong, precise, and inescapable. When He decides to seize someone, no power can prevent it. The delay is not negligence but strategy. Those who think they have outsmarted divine justice will discover that Allah's plan was working all along, leading them exactly where He intended."
  },
  184: {
    "Have they not ever given it a thought?": "Allah challenges the disbelievers to simply think. Critical thinking and honest reflection would lead them to truth. But many people refuse to think deeply about life's fundamental questions, preferring comfortable ignorance over challenging truth.",
    "Their fellow man is not insane.": "The Quraysh accused Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) of being crazy. But Allah invites them to reflect—they knew him for forty years before prophethood. He was known as Al-Amin (the Trustworthy) and As-Sadiq (the Truthful). His character, wisdom, and consistency all testified to his sanity and integrity. A madman could not have transformed society, established a civilization, and delivered such profound guidance.",
    "He is only sent with a clear warning.": "The Prophet's mission is straightforward—he warns people of the consequences of disbelief and sin. His message is clear, not confusing or contradictory. A sincere evaluation of his message would reveal its truth and coherence."
  },
  185: {
    "Have they ever reflected on the wonders of the heavens and the earth,": "Allah invites deep contemplation of the universe. The vastness of space, the precision of celestial movements, the complexity of Earth's ecosystems—all point to an intelligent, powerful Creator. Scientific discovery should increase awe of Allah, not diminish it.",
    "and everything Allah has created,": "Beyond the grand scale, even the smallest creations testify to Allah's power and wisdom. The structure of an atom, the design of a cell, the instincts of animals—every created thing bears witness to its Creator. Those who truly look cannot miss the signs.",
    "and that perhaps their end is near?": "Death could come at any moment. This urgency should motivate reflection and action. Why waste time in denial when life is so uncertain? The opportunity to believe and repent may end without warning.",
    "So what message after this ˹Quran˺ would they believe in?": "If people reject the Quran—the most clear, comprehensive, and miraculous guidance ever revealed—what else could possibly convince them? The Quran is the ultimate proof. Those who reject it have no excuse and no alternative that could be clearer or more compelling."
  },
  186: {
    "Whoever Allah allows to stray, none can guide,": "When Allah, based on a person's choices, allows them to remain astray, no one can guide them. All the arguments, proofs, and sincere advice in the world cannot penetrate a heart that Allah has sealed due to its persistent rejection of truth.",
    "leaving them to wander blindly in their defiance.": "Such people are left in their transgression, stumbling around without direction. They think they see clearly, but they are spiritually blind. Their rebellion has become their prison, and they wander in it without hope of escape—unless they themselves sincerely turn back to Allah."
  },
  187: {
    "They ask you ˹O Prophet˺ regarding the Hour, \"When will it be?\"": "People repeatedly asked the Prophet about the timing of the Day of Judgment. This question often came from mockers who wanted to challenge him or doubters who thought demanding a date would expose him. Human curiosity about the end times is natural, but the exact timing is not ours to know.",
    "Say, \"That knowledge is only with my Lord.": "The Prophet is commanded to clearly state that knowledge of the Hour is exclusively with Allah. Not even the greatest prophets or closest angels know when it will occur. This is part of the unseen that Allah has kept for Himself.",
    "He alone will reveal it when the time comes.": "Only Allah will manifest the Hour when He decrees. No one can predict, calculate, or deduce its timing. Those who claim to know specific dates are lying—this knowledge belongs to Allah alone.",
    "It is too tremendous for the heavens and the earth": "The Hour is so momentous that the entire creation dreads it. The heavens and earth, despite their vastness, are shaken by its weight and significance. Everything will be transformed when it arrives.",
    "and will only take you by surprise.\"": "It will come suddenly, without warning signs that allow preparation at the last moment. People will be going about their daily lives—buying, selling, eating, sleeping—when suddenly it arrives. This uncertainty should keep believers in constant readiness.",
    "They ask you as if you had full knowledge of it.": "The questioners persisted as if the Prophet were hiding information from them. But he was genuinely unaware of the timing, just as they were.",
    "Say, \"That knowledge is only with Allah, but most people do not know.\"": "The Prophet reiterates that this knowledge is Allah's alone. Most people don't understand why this information is withheld—it's actually a mercy. If people knew the exact time, they might delay repentance until the last moment. The uncertainty encourages constant preparedness."
  },
  188: {
    "Say, \"I have no power to benefit or protect myself, except by the Will of Allah.": "The Prophet declares his complete dependence on Allah. Despite being the greatest of creation, he cannot bring benefit or ward off harm from himself without Allah's permission. This establishes that he is human, not divine, and that all power belongs to Allah alone.",
    "If I had known the unknown, I would have benefited myself enormously, and no harm would have ever touched me.": "The Prophet presents logical proof that he doesn't know the unseen. If he did, he would have avoided every loss, prevented every difficulty, and maximized every opportunity. But he experienced hardship, loss, and challenges like any human—proving that the unseen is hidden from him too.",
    "I am only a warner and deliverer of good news for those who believe.\"": "The Prophet clarifies his role—he warns of consequences for disbelief and brings good news of reward for faith. He is a messenger, not a controller of the universe. His job is to convey, not to compel or to possess supernatural powers of his own."
  },
  189: {
    "He is the One Who created you from a single soul,": "Allah created all humanity from Adam, a single soul. This establishes human unity—we all share the same origin and are fundamentally equal. Race, nationality, and status are secondary; our shared humanity comes first.",
    "then from it made its spouse so he may find comfort in her.": "Allah created Hawwa (Eve) from Adam to be his companion. Marriage is designed for tranquility and comfort—spouses are meant to find peace and rest in each other. This is part of Allah's mercy and design for human happiness.",
    "After he had been united with her, she carried a light burden that developed gradually.": "When conception occurs, the pregnancy begins light and unnoticed. The early stages are easy to bear. This describes the natural progression of pregnancy that Allah designed.",
    "When it grew heavy, they prayed to Allah, their Lord,": "As the pregnancy progressed and became difficult, the couple turned to Allah in desperate supplication. This is natural human behavior—in moments of need and fear, people instinctively call upon their Creator.",
    "\"If you grant us good offspring, we will certainly be grateful.\"": "They made a promise to Allah: if He blessed them with a healthy child, they would be grateful and devoted. This kind of conditional promise is common in human supplication—bargaining with Allah in moments of desperation."
  },
  190: {
    "But when He granted their descendants good offspring,": "Allah answered their prayers and blessed them (or their descendants throughout human history) with healthy children. The blessing they desperately sought was given.",
    "they associated false gods in what He has given them.": "Instead of fulfilling their promise of gratitude, they began attributing the blessing to other than Allah. They associated partners with Allah in the very blessing He had given them—naming children after idols, attributing success to false gods, or believing other forces were responsible for their good fortune. This describes a pattern that repeats throughout human history.",
    "Exalted is Allah above what they associate ˹with Him˺!": "Allah declares Himself far above and free from their false associations. He is the sole giver of all blessings, and attributing them to others is a grave injustice and falsehood. Allah does not share His attributes or rights with anyone."
  },
  191: {
    "Do they associate ˹with Allah˺ those ˹idols˺ which cannot create anything,": "Allah poses a rhetorical question exposing the absurdity of idol worship. These idols cannot create even the smallest thing—not an atom, not a fly, not anything. Creation is Allah's exclusive domain.",
    "but are in fact created;": "The idols themselves are created objects—carved by human hands from wood, stone, or metal. How can something created be worthy of worship? The created can never be equal to the Creator. This basic logic should be enough to demolish idol worship."
  },
  192: {
    "which cannot help them, or even help themselves?": "These false gods cannot assist their worshippers in any way. They cannot answer prayers, provide protection, or grant benefits. Even more telling—they cannot even help themselves. If someone attacks or destroys an idol, it cannot defend itself. How can something so helpless be worthy of worship?"
  },
  193: {
    "And if you ˹idolaters˺ call upon them for guidance, they cannot respond to you.": "If you ask these idols for direction in life, for answers to your problems, or for guidance on the right path, they remain utterly silent. They have no wisdom to share, no guidance to offer.",
    "It is all the same whether you call them or remain silent.": "Praying to idols and not praying produces exactly the same result—nothing. They cannot hear, understand, or respond. The elaborate rituals and desperate prayers directed at false gods are completely futile."
  },
  194: {
    "Those ˹idols˺ you invoke besides Allah are created beings like yourselves.": "Whatever you worship besides Allah—whether statues, humans, angels, or any creation—they are servants of Allah just like you. They have no divine power or authority. Worshipping them is like worshipping your equal or even your inferior.",
    "So call upon them and see if they will answer you, if your claims are true!": "Allah issues a direct challenge. If idol worshippers truly believe their gods have power, let them prove it. Call upon them and see if they respond. This challenge exposes the emptiness of their beliefs. Throughout history, no idol has ever answered a prayer or performed a miracle."
  },
  195: {
    "Do they have feet to walk with?": "Allah points out that these idols lack even the basic faculties that humans possess. They cannot walk to come to anyone's aid. They are stationary, lifeless objects.",
    "Or hands to hold with?": "They have no hands to grasp things, to give, to defend, or to act in any way. Carved hands are not real hands.",
    "Or eyes to see with?": "They cannot see their worshippers, witness their devotion, or observe their needs. Painted eyes are not real eyes.",
    "Or ears to hear with?": "They cannot hear the prayers, cries, and pleas directed at them. Stone ears are not real ears.",
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"Call upon your associate-gods and conspire against me without delay!": "The Prophet is told to boldly challenge the idol worshippers. If their gods have any power, let them join together with their idols and try to harm the Prophet. Don't hesitate—do it immediately! This confident challenge demonstrates complete trust in Allah and exposes the powerlessness of false gods."
  },
  196: {
    "\"Indeed, my Protector is Allah Who has revealed this Book.": "The Prophet declares his complete reliance on Allah alone. Allah, who revealed the Quran, is his guardian, helper, and protector. The one who sent down the Book is fully capable of protecting its messenger. This statement of trust demonstrates where true security comes from.",
    "For He ˹alone˺ protects the righteous.": "Allah's protection extends to all who are righteous. Those who obey Him, follow His guidance, and maintain their integrity can count on His guardianship. Being under Allah's protection is the greatest security—no force can harm someone whom Allah protects."
  },
  197: {
    "But those ˹false gods˺ you call besides Him can neither help you nor even themselves.\"": "In stark contrast to Allah's perfect protection, false gods offer nothing. They cannot assist their worshippers in any way—not in this life, not in the Hereafter. They cannot even protect themselves from destruction or decay. Relying on them is utterly futile."
  },
  198: {
    "If you ˹idolaters˺ call them to guidance, they cannot hear.": "Even if you tried to guide the idols themselves to the right path, they cannot hear your words. They are inanimate objects without the capacity for understanding. The absurdity is turned around—not only can they not guide you, but you cannot even guide them!",
    "And you ˹O Prophet˺ may see them facing towards you, but they cannot see.": "The idols may be positioned as if looking, with carved eyes directed forward, but they see nothing. Their apparent gaze is an illusion. They have no awareness, consciousness, or perception. This serves as a final emphatic point about their complete lifelessness."
  },
  199: {
    "Be gracious,": "Allah commands the Prophet—and by extension, all believers—to practice forgiveness and leniency with people. Accept what is easy from them, don't demand perfection, and pardon their shortcomings. This creates harmony in relationships and prevents unnecessary conflict.",
    "enjoin what is right,": "Continue commanding good and promoting virtue. The believer's responsibility to encourage righteousness never ends. This should be done with wisdom, kindness, and appropriate to each situation, but it must not be abandoned.",
    "and turn away from those who act ignorantly.": "When foolish people provoke, insult, or act stupidly, the best response is to disengage. Don't lower yourself to their level. Arguing with the ignorant only wastes time and energy. Walk away with dignity and preserve your peace. This isn't weakness—it's wisdom and self-control."
  },
  200: {
    "If you are tempted by Satan,": "Satan constantly tries to influence believers, provoking anger, lust, pride, despair, and other negative impulses. These whispers and promptings are his primary weapons against humanity. Recognizing these temptations as satanic is the first step to resisting them.",
    "then seek refuge with Allah.": "The prescribed defense against Satan is to seek Allah's protection. Say 'A'udhu billahi min ash-shaytanir rajeem' (I seek refuge in Allah from the accursed Satan). This simple act connects you to divine protection and breaks Satan's influence. It acknowledges your weakness and Allah's power.",
    "Surely He is All-Hearing, All-Knowing.": "Allah hears your plea for protection and knows exactly what you're facing. He is aware of Satan's schemes and your struggles. His hearing and knowledge ensure that your seeking refuge is never in vain—He responds to those who call upon Him."
  },
  201: {
    "Indeed, when Satan whispers to those mindful ˹of Allah˺,": "Even the most pious people are not immune to Satan's whispers. The difference is in how they respond. Those with taqwa (consciousness of Allah) are affected momentarily but quickly recover.",
    "they remember ˹their Lord˺": "When satanic thoughts touch them, they immediately remember Allah. This remembrance might be through seeking refuge, reciting Quran, making dhikr, or simply becoming aware that this impulse is from Satan. Remembrance of Allah is the antidote to satanic influence.",
    "then they start to see ˹things˺ clearly.": "Once they remember Allah, clarity returns. They see the situation for what it is—a trap from Satan—and they regain their spiritual vision. The fog of temptation lifts, and they can make righteous choices again. This is the cycle of the believer: momentary slip, remembrance, clarity, and return to obedience."
  },
  202: {
    "But the devils persistently plunge their ˹human˺ associates deeper into wickedness,": "In contrast to the believers who recover, those who ally themselves with Satan are pulled deeper into sin. The devils—both jinn and their human allies—continuously drag their victims further into misguidance. Each sin makes the next one easier.",
    "sparing no effort.": "Satan and his allies never give up or take breaks in their mission of corruption. They work tirelessly, using every tool at their disposal. This relentless nature of evil should motivate believers to be equally persistent in their pursuit of righteousness."
  },
  203: {
    "If you ˹O Prophet˺ do not bring them a sign ˹which they demanded˺,": "The disbelievers constantly demanded specific miracles of their choosing—make a spring gush forth, turn this mountain to gold, bring angels we can see. When the Prophet didn't produce their requested signs, they complained.",
    "they ask, \"Why do you not make it yourself?\"": "They mocked him, suggesting he should just create miracles himself if he were really a prophet. This revealed their misunderstanding—prophets don't perform miracles by their own power; miracles come only from Allah according to His will.",
    "Say, \"I only follow what is revealed to me from my Lord.": "The Prophet clarifies his role—he follows divine revelation, he doesn't manufacture it. He cannot produce miracles on demand or modify the message to please people. His job is to convey what Allah reveals, nothing more and nothing less.",
    "This ˹Quran˺ is an insight from your Lord—": "The Quran itself is the greatest miracle and source of insight. It provides vision to see truth from falsehood, guidance for every situation, and understanding of existence's deepest questions. Those who seek signs should recognize the Quran as the ultimate sign.",
    "a guide and a mercy for those who believe.\"": "For believers, the Quran is both guidance (showing the way) and mercy (bringing blessing and protection). But these benefits are realized only by those who believe. Without faith, even the greatest guidance remains unappreciated."
  },
  204: {
    "When the Quran is recited, listen to it attentively": "Allah commands us to give the Quran our full attention when it is being recited. This means actively listening with the heart and mind engaged, trying to understand and reflect on what is being said. This applies particularly during prayer when the imam recites, but also in other settings where Quran is being read aloud.",
    "and be silent,": "Along with listening comes silence—not just quiet lips but quiet hearts. We should not talk, make noise, or allow our minds to wander during Quran recitation. This silence is a form of respect for Allah's words and creates the space for the message to penetrate the heart.",
    "so you may be shown mercy.": "The reward for proper attention to the Quran is divine mercy. Listening attentively opens the heart to receive guidance and blessing. Those who honor Allah's words by giving them attention will find Allah honoring them with His mercy."
  },
  205: {
    "Remember your Lord inwardly": "Dhikr (remembrance of Allah) should be done in the heart, not just on the tongue. Internal remembrance is more sincere and profound. When your heart remembers Allah, your entire being is oriented toward Him.",
    "with humility and reverence": "The remembrance should be accompanied by proper emotions—humble neediness before Allah and fear of His displeasure. This is not casual or mechanical repetition but heartfelt connection with the Creator.",
    "and in a moderate tone of voice,": "When dhikr is vocalized, it should be moderate—not too loud showing off, and not completely silent. A gentle, moderate voice reflects proper etiquette before Allah. Loud, public displays often indicate desire for human attention rather than divine connection.",
    "both morning and evening.": "Dhikr should be practiced regularly, particularly in the blessed times of morning and evening. These are optimal times for remembrance when the atmosphere is calm and the heart is receptive. The Prophet (peace be upon him) taught specific adhkar for these times.",
    "And do not be one of the heedless.": "The verse ends with a warning against heedlessness. Forgetting Allah and becoming absorbed in worldly matters is a spiritual disease. Regular dhikr is the cure that keeps the heart alive and connected to its Creator. Those who neglect remembrance become spiritually dead even while physically alive."
  },
  206: {
    "Surely those ˹angels˺ nearest to your Lord are not too proud to worship Him.": "The angels, despite their nobility, closeness to Allah, and freedom from sin, never consider themselves above worship. These magnificent beings, created from light and given tremendous abilities, worship Allah constantly without any arrogance. If they are not too proud to worship, how could any human be?",
    "They glorify Him.": "The angels continuously declare Allah's perfection and freedom from any deficiency. Their glorification never ceases—they never tire or become bored of praising their Lord. This is their joy and purpose.",
    "And to Him they prostrate.": "The angels prostrate to Allah in ultimate submission and humility. Prostration is the position of greatest humility, placing the face on the ground before the Creator. The surah ends with this image of complete surrender, inviting humans to join the angels in worship. This verse is one of the places where prostration (sujood at-tilawah) is recommended when reciting or hearing the Quran."
  }
};